WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.650 --> 00:00:02.220
- Good morning, everyone.

00:00:02.220 --> 00:00:04.280
I'm Tomiko Brown-Nagin,
the dean of the Radcliffe

00:00:04.280 --> 00:00:05.750
Institute for Advanced Study.

00:00:05.750 --> 00:00:09.650
And I'm so pleased to
welcome you all here today

00:00:09.650 --> 00:00:14.390
for this important convening
on unsettled citizens.

00:00:14.390 --> 00:00:18.050
Citizenship rights,
or the lack thereof,

00:00:18.050 --> 00:00:21.230
affect individuals,
families, and communities

00:00:21.230 --> 00:00:23.990
in very concrete ways.

00:00:23.990 --> 00:00:26.060
Citizenship also
shapes our sense

00:00:26.060 --> 00:00:29.720
of identity and
belonging, so much so

00:00:29.720 --> 00:00:32.000
that many people tend
to think of citizenship

00:00:32.000 --> 00:00:37.100
as immutable, or at the
very least, as settled.

00:00:37.100 --> 00:00:40.490
And yet, as we'll explore
today, many individuals

00:00:40.490 --> 00:00:43.910
find that their citizenship
is quite unsettled.

00:00:43.910 --> 00:00:47.360
Consider, for example,
the US territories.

00:00:47.360 --> 00:00:51.920
Later today, we'll hear from
Mayor Carmen YulÃ­n Cruz Soto

00:00:51.920 --> 00:00:53.225
of San Juan, Puerto Rico.

00:00:55.850 --> 00:00:58.670
And as we hear from her,
we should bear in mind

00:00:58.670 --> 00:01:03.200
that people born in her city,
like nearly four million others

00:01:03.200 --> 00:01:06.050
across Puerto Rico,
Guam, the US Virgin

00:01:06.050 --> 00:01:09.440
Islands, and the northern
Mariana Islands, formerly

00:01:09.440 --> 00:01:13.370
lack full protection
under the US constitution

00:01:13.370 --> 00:01:17.880
despite birthright
American citizenship.

00:01:17.880 --> 00:01:20.940
And American Samoans
as US nationals

00:01:20.940 --> 00:01:24.000
enjoy neither full
citizenship rights

00:01:24.000 --> 00:01:27.000
nor full constitutional rights.

00:01:27.000 --> 00:01:30.630
These facts aren't
well understood.

00:01:30.630 --> 00:01:35.110
In the fall of 2017,
after Hurricane Maria,

00:01:35.110 --> 00:01:38.040
the New York Times ran an
article under the headline

00:01:38.040 --> 00:01:43.980
"Nearly Half of Americans Don't
Know Puerto Ricans Are Fellow

00:01:43.980 --> 00:01:45.390
Citizens."

00:01:45.390 --> 00:01:49.110
What's more, the federal
government's response to Maria

00:01:49.110 --> 00:01:51.720
did not fully
reflect the reality

00:01:51.720 --> 00:01:57.660
that the hurricane caused a
domestic humanitarian crisis.

00:01:57.660 --> 00:02:01.110
Just 13 days after the
hurricane made landfall,

00:02:01.110 --> 00:02:04.530
President Trump visited
Puerto Rico and said,

00:02:04.530 --> 00:02:06.730
"I hate to tell
you, Puerto Rico,

00:02:06.730 --> 00:02:10.350
but you've thrown our budget
a little out of whack."

00:02:10.350 --> 00:02:12.150
[LAUGHTER]

00:02:12.150 --> 00:02:14.385
Language that seemingly
defined Puerto Ricans

00:02:14.385 --> 00:02:17.820
as other, not a part of us.

00:02:17.820 --> 00:02:20.400
Later, in an interview,
he lamented--

00:02:20.400 --> 00:02:22.530
and I'll quote him again--

00:02:22.530 --> 00:02:27.180
"Instead of getting in thank
you, we got bad publicity,"

00:02:27.180 --> 00:02:30.630
as if fulfilling the nation's
obligations to Puerto Rico

00:02:30.630 --> 00:02:36.000
merited special gratitude
from the islanders.

00:02:36.000 --> 00:02:38.250
Now, it's a century
old legal doctrine

00:02:38.250 --> 00:02:42.210
that underlines why the US
territories enjoy only limited

00:02:42.210 --> 00:02:44.340
constitutional protections.

00:02:44.340 --> 00:02:48.420
And this doctrine emerged
when law and official policy

00:02:48.420 --> 00:02:51.900
were steeped in the
ideologies of white supremacy

00:02:51.900 --> 00:02:54.270
and colonialism.

00:02:54.270 --> 00:02:57.300
Just five years after
the US Supreme Court

00:02:57.300 --> 00:03:01.200
upheld racial segregation
in the 1896 case of Plessy

00:03:01.200 --> 00:03:03.720
versus Ferguson,
the court started

00:03:03.720 --> 00:03:05.910
to issue decisions
that differentiated

00:03:05.910 --> 00:03:09.720
between incorporated territories
that would officially

00:03:09.720 --> 00:03:12.750
get statehood like
Arizona and New

00:03:12.750 --> 00:03:15.480
Mexico and unincorporated
territories

00:03:15.480 --> 00:03:19.530
like Puerto Rico that would not.

00:03:19.530 --> 00:03:22.800
This doctrine, which
is still in place,

00:03:22.800 --> 00:03:26.670
holds that territories acquired
in and following the Spanish

00:03:26.670 --> 00:03:30.150
American War belong
to but aren't

00:03:30.150 --> 00:03:33.570
a part of the United States.

00:03:33.570 --> 00:03:36.360
This entirely constructed
difference help

00:03:36.360 --> 00:03:38.820
explains why Americans
in the territories

00:03:38.820 --> 00:03:42.480
can, for instance,
serve in the military

00:03:42.480 --> 00:03:48.260
but can't vote in
national elections.

00:03:48.260 --> 00:03:53.520
American citizenship is
then decidedly unsettled.

00:03:53.520 --> 00:03:56.820
As immutable as it
may sometimes seem,

00:03:56.820 --> 00:03:59.040
citizenship is constructed.

00:03:59.040 --> 00:04:01.380
And it's often directly
linked to histories

00:04:01.380 --> 00:04:05.940
of colonialism, discrimination,
and class distinction.

00:04:05.940 --> 00:04:08.820
This conference will wrestle
with several examples

00:04:08.820 --> 00:04:12.070
of unsettled citizens and
unsettled citizenship.

00:04:12.070 --> 00:04:16.380
It is a crucial, and it is an
urgent conversation, especially

00:04:16.380 --> 00:04:18.620
now.

00:04:18.620 --> 00:04:21.769
A conference like this isn't
possible without the efforts

