00:07:45.550 --> 00:07:48.940
Our word "citizen" in English
and its equivalent in other

00:07:48.940 --> 00:07:53.110
European languages derives
from the Latin "civitas,"

00:07:53.110 --> 00:07:56.440
"the city," or more
properly, "city-state."

00:07:56.440 --> 00:07:58.780
It is that city-state
and that community

00:07:58.780 --> 00:08:01.630
which defines and
regulates citizenship,

00:08:01.630 --> 00:08:05.350
and citizenship which in
turn composes, reconstitutes,

00:08:05.350 --> 00:08:08.890
and reforms the city.

00:08:08.890 --> 00:08:12.130
We start with a panel on
economics citizenship.

00:08:12.130 --> 00:08:15.340
The communities that defined
and awards citizenship

00:08:15.340 --> 00:08:20.290
are also engines of social
and material wealth creation.

00:08:20.290 --> 00:08:23.020
And the relationship of
community belonging to wealth

00:08:23.020 --> 00:08:26.020
has always raised important
and sometimes troubling

00:08:26.020 --> 00:08:28.790
dimensions of conflict.

00:08:28.790 --> 00:08:32.210
Do the duties and rights
attendant to citizenship

00:08:32.210 --> 00:08:35.299
require a minimal level
of material wealth

00:08:35.299 --> 00:08:37.669
in order for their realization?

00:08:37.669 --> 00:08:39.950
If so, how much wealth?

00:08:39.950 --> 00:08:42.559
What variety of goods?

00:08:42.559 --> 00:08:47.630
Do concentrations of wealth
properly acquire citizenship?

00:08:47.630 --> 00:08:52.670
If so, should that citizenship
be limited or fully free?

00:08:52.670 --> 00:08:55.730
The Supreme Court case,
as many of you know,

00:08:55.730 --> 00:08:57.920
that endowed corporations
with free speech

00:08:57.920 --> 00:09:01.400
rights sufficient to strike down
a set of federal contribution

00:09:01.400 --> 00:09:04.100
limits and campaigns
was entitled,

00:09:04.100 --> 00:09:07.040
in all of its delicious
and disturbing irony,

00:09:07.040 --> 00:09:12.400
Citizens United versus the
Federal Election Commission.

00:09:12.400 --> 00:09:16.330
But corporations are far more
than concentrations of capital.

00:09:16.330 --> 00:09:19.150
Harvard is a corporation.

00:09:19.150 --> 00:09:22.030
And this corporation lobbies.

00:09:22.030 --> 00:09:24.280
And as we're pleased to hear
from our wonderful guest

00:09:24.280 --> 00:09:27.310
from Alaska momentarily,
Rosita Worl,

00:09:27.310 --> 00:09:30.970
Alaska native corporations
are corporations.

00:09:30.970 --> 00:09:35.470
And so these are often
more complicated issues

00:09:35.470 --> 00:09:37.750
than they might seem.

00:09:37.750 --> 00:09:39.700
We next move to a
panel on citizenship

00:09:39.700 --> 00:09:41.440
and its gatekeepers.

00:09:41.440 --> 00:09:44.830
Citizenship does not descend
like manna from heaven

00:09:44.830 --> 00:09:45.760
but is made on earth.

00:09:45.760 --> 00:09:49.090
It is a human construct,
humanly fashioned.

00:09:49.090 --> 00:09:51.490
The community determines
the rules of citizenship

00:09:51.490 --> 00:09:53.530
and how they are applied.

00:09:53.530 --> 00:09:56.020
So how do indigenous
nations, for instance,

00:09:56.020 --> 00:10:00.100
regulate belonging based on
aspects of race, genetics,

00:10:00.100 --> 00:10:02.710
and the calculus
of blood quantum?

00:10:02.710 --> 00:10:04.600
How do modern states
such as France

00:10:04.600 --> 00:10:07.990
shape citizenship based
upon language, race,

00:10:07.990 --> 00:10:10.090
and cultural belonging?

00:10:10.090 --> 00:10:12.670
And what happens when
nations grant citizenship

00:10:12.670 --> 00:10:17.170
to those previously considered
external to its community,

00:10:17.170 --> 00:10:19.150
but who have been
let in at some level

00:10:19.150 --> 00:10:22.570
because they provided an
alliance or some service?

00:10:22.570 --> 00:10:24.490
The case of the Hmong
in the United States

00:10:24.490 --> 00:10:27.610
provides a window
into these questions.

