in the nation state
to social provision

00:14:21.360 --> 00:14:26.060
within and across the
boundaries of nation states;

00:14:26.060 --> 00:14:28.640
the emergence of
questions prompted

00:14:28.640 --> 00:14:30.950
by new forms of knowledge--

00:14:30.950 --> 00:14:33.860
scholarly knowledge--
most famously,

00:14:33.860 --> 00:14:37.490
the research of Piketty
and Saez on the history

00:14:37.490 --> 00:14:39.200
of economic inequality.

00:14:39.200 --> 00:14:42.140
But there's been an
outpouring of scholarship

00:14:42.140 --> 00:14:44.720
in many, many fields
on the question

00:14:44.720 --> 00:14:47.940
of economics citizenship
over the last decade.

00:14:47.940 --> 00:14:50.690
And then law, my own field.

00:14:50.690 --> 00:14:52.820
As Professor carpenter
noted, there's

00:14:52.820 --> 00:14:56.930
been a sustained debate in
light of the Citizens United

00:14:56.930 --> 00:15:00.860
decision over the ability of
corporations and the wealthy

00:15:00.860 --> 00:15:05.660
to mold the contours of
citizenship to their liking.

00:15:05.660 --> 00:15:10.880
Economic citizenship obviously
is also an old question.

00:15:10.880 --> 00:15:14.900
It's been debated over
and over across the world

00:15:14.900 --> 00:15:18.380
ever since the advent of
the transition to the system

00:15:18.380 --> 00:15:21.140
that we now call capitalism.

00:15:21.140 --> 00:15:24.430
And ever since the emergence
of modern nation states

00:15:24.430 --> 00:15:27.950
that made questions of
citizenship and membership

00:15:27.950 --> 00:15:30.920
of all kinds paramount.

00:15:30.920 --> 00:15:33.800
Now, today's panel
is uniquely qualified

00:15:33.800 --> 00:15:36.080
to probe questions of
economic citizenship

00:15:36.080 --> 00:15:38.390
that have emerged
in our own time

00:15:38.390 --> 00:15:40.640
in light of the long
history of such questions

00:15:40.640 --> 00:15:44.630
being raised, and
also equally qualified

00:15:44.630 --> 00:15:48.620
to question the conventional
contours of the debate

00:15:48.620 --> 00:15:51.013
about economic
citizenship, including

00:15:51.013 --> 00:15:52.430
the conventional
markers that I've

00:15:52.430 --> 00:15:56.500
outlined in this introduction.

00:15:56.500 --> 00:16:00.730
I'm going to introduce them
just by title and the names

00:16:00.730 --> 00:16:02.830
of their most prominent works.

00:16:02.830 --> 00:16:06.730
You can find greater
biographical summaries

00:16:06.730 --> 00:16:11.400
of their accomplishments,
which are many, in the program.

00:16:11.400 --> 00:16:13.150
Our first speaker is
going to be K. Sabeel

00:16:13.150 --> 00:16:15.640
Rahman, who's Associate
Professor of Law

00:16:15.640 --> 00:16:17.200
at Brooklyn Law School.

00:16:17.200 --> 00:16:19.720
He's the author of Democracy
Against Domination, Oxford

00:16:19.720 --> 00:16:23.770
University Press 2017 and
the forthcoming Civic Power

00:16:23.770 --> 00:16:27.710
from Cambridge University Press.

