00:17:24.267 --> 00:17:29.580
[APPLAUSE]

00:17:29.580 --> 00:17:32.455
Thank you so much, Ken, and
Dean Brown-Nagin, and Radcliffe,

00:17:32.455 --> 00:17:33.330
and to our panelists.

00:17:33.330 --> 00:17:35.860
Really excited for this
day and this discussion.

00:17:35.860 --> 00:17:39.158
So as Professor Mack was
saying, I mean, this really

00:17:39.158 --> 00:17:41.700
is such a timely moment to be
thinking about these questions.

00:17:41.700 --> 00:17:43.950
And coming into this
panel this morning,

00:17:43.950 --> 00:17:46.710
I was thinking about
the real live fights

00:17:46.710 --> 00:17:48.390
over economic
citizenship playing out

00:17:48.390 --> 00:17:51.570
in so many parts of the country
and around the world, fights

00:17:51.570 --> 00:17:56.790
over the water crisis in
Flint, or over the burning

00:17:56.790 --> 00:18:00.210
of gentrification in cities
like New York or San Francisco

00:18:00.210 --> 00:18:03.000
or Boston even,
the Fight for $15,

00:18:03.000 --> 00:18:05.890
and the changing nature of
war, just to name a few.

00:18:05.890 --> 00:18:07.710
And I name that at
the beginning to say

00:18:07.710 --> 00:18:11.230
that what we're talking
about here is real life.

00:18:11.230 --> 00:18:15.750
And it's not just about kind of
abstract notions of inequality

00:18:15.750 --> 00:18:16.830
and membership.

00:18:16.830 --> 00:18:18.900
But these are
political fights that

00:18:18.900 --> 00:18:21.900
are playing out on many
different terrains of context.

00:18:21.900 --> 00:18:23.670
And so for my
remarks here, I want

00:18:23.670 --> 00:18:25.510
to sketch out three things.

00:18:25.510 --> 00:18:29.070
One is just to unpack a little
bit the different dimensions

00:18:29.070 --> 00:18:30.360
of economic citizenship.

00:18:30.360 --> 00:18:33.660
So we're used to thinking about
economic inequality, wages

00:18:33.660 --> 00:18:34.500
and income.

00:18:34.500 --> 00:18:36.362
But there's really
much more going on

00:18:36.362 --> 00:18:37.320
underneath the surface.

00:18:37.320 --> 00:18:39.360
And want to kind
of lay that out.

00:18:39.360 --> 00:18:44.790
Second is to make the claim
that economic citizenship

00:18:44.790 --> 00:18:46.860
or citizenship more
broadly is not just

00:18:46.860 --> 00:18:48.940
a legal category and
an on/off switch.

00:18:48.940 --> 00:18:51.420
But I think really all of
us are, in different ways,

00:18:51.420 --> 00:18:54.270
understanding citizenship
as a functional concept,

00:18:54.270 --> 00:18:55.673
that it's really a spectrum.

00:18:55.673 --> 00:18:57.090
There are all these
different ways

00:18:57.090 --> 00:19:01.140
in which law and policy
and politics construct

00:19:01.140 --> 00:19:03.040
different levels of membership.

00:19:03.040 --> 00:19:06.480
Who gets to be a full member
with full and equal dignity

00:19:06.480 --> 00:19:11.070
and standing in this society
is a topic of contestation.

00:19:11.070 --> 00:19:13.810
And then the third, to say
a little bit about the how.

00:19:13.810 --> 00:19:19.080
So what are the combinations of
ideas, institutional changes,

00:19:19.080 --> 00:19:23.430
movement politics that are
needed to change our scope

00:19:23.430 --> 00:19:26.835
and understandings of
economic citizenship?

00:19:26.835 --> 00:19:27.960
So let me start at the top.

00:19:27.960 --> 00:19:30.930
So Professor Mack
mentioned the new research

00:19:30.930 --> 00:19:34.493
on inequality, the work of
Piketty and Saez and others.

00:19:34.493 --> 00:19:35.910
And I think that's
absolutely been

00:19:35.910 --> 00:19:39.730
central to the opening up of
the academic conversation.

00:19:39.730 --> 00:19:42.150
But if we think back through
the political contestation

00:19:42.150 --> 00:19:44.610
over academic citizenship
now and in the course

00:19:44.610 --> 00:19:48.900
of American history, I'd argue
that the central concept is not

00:19:48.900 --> 00:19:51.840
just inequality, but
really the problem of power

00:19:51.840 --> 00:19:53.190
and domination.

00:19:53.190 --> 00:19:58.560
So if you flashback, say, 100
years, the late 19th century,

00:19:58.560 --> 00:20:02.040
the populist parties
gathering in Kansas in 1892.

00:20:02.040 --> 00:20:04.080
And they issue their
party platform,

00:20:04.080 --> 00:20:07.320
and it's styled as a second
Declaration of Independence.

00:20:07.320 --> 00:20:11.010
Modeled on Jefferson's,
but where in place

00:20:11.010 --> 00:20:14.190
of the sovereign-- the sovereign
monarch against which democracy

00:20:14.190 --> 00:20:15.570
has to rise up--

00:20:15.570 --> 00:20:19.410
here, the framing is liberation
from the concentrated

00:20:19.410 --> 00:20:24.450
economic power of the new
corporate titans of then

00:20:24.450 --> 00:20:26.000
the first Gilded Age.

00:20:26.000 --> 00:20:29.310
So this is the era of J. P.
Morgan, the man, not the firm.

00:20:29.310 --> 00:20:33.360
But still just as terrifying
then as it perhaps is now.

00:20:33.360 --> 00:20:35.910
And Vanderbilt and the
railroads and all of the rest.

00:20:35.910 --> 00:20:39.160
But the argument here
was that as citizens,

00:20:39.160 --> 00:20:41.340
as economic citizens,
people could not

00:20:41.340 --> 00:20:45.840
be free when they live under
the effective subjugation

00:20:45.840 --> 00:20:50.220
of private power, private firms
that can essentially govern

00:20:50.220 --> 00:20:52.590
the economy for
their own interest

00:20:52.590 --> 00:20:54.870
and in their own profit
without the kinds of checks

00:20:54.870 --> 00:20:59.010
and balances that we expect of
any form of sovereign power.

00:20:59.010 --> 00:21:02.910
And so there is a broadening
of the idea of democracy

00:21:02.910 --> 00:21:05.250
and citizenship and
membership to take

00:21:05.250 --> 00:21:07.590
on the problem of private power.

00:21:07.590 --> 00:21:10.200
Let me give another example,
more contemporary one.

00:21:10.200 --> 00:21:13.200
If we think about the
fights over urban inequality

00:21:13.200 --> 00:21:17.310
in recent years, Matt
Desmond's work on eviction,

00:21:17.310 --> 00:21:22.690
fights over the rise of housing
prices in New York and Boston,

00:21:22.690 --> 00:21:25.890
San Francisco, part of
what's going on here I think

00:21:25.890 --> 00:21:28.780
is about economic power
and economic membership,

00:21:28.780 --> 00:21:31.320
but in a more subtle way.

00:21:31.320 --> 00:21:33.450
Research shows that the
neighborhood that you're

00:21:33.450 --> 00:21:37.800
born in has intergenerational
effects on your wealth,

00:21:37.800 --> 00:21:39.690
your well-being, your health.

00:21:39.690 --> 00:21:44.080
And the rules that govern
where construction happens,

00:21:44.080 --> 00:21:46.690
how cities are zoned,
who lives where,

00:21:46.690 --> 00:21:48.940
where transportation
infrastructure lies,

00:21:48.940 --> 00:21:51.120
it's all very kind
of behind the scenes.

00:21:51.120 --> 00:21:53.720
But we have effectively
constructed--

00:21:53.720 --> 00:21:57.900
or rather reconstructed an
even more egregious form

00:21:57.900 --> 00:22:01.710
of segregation through
our urban policies

00:22:01.710 --> 00:22:04.110
than what we had in
the era of Jim Crow

00:22:04.110 --> 00:22:06.852
and prior to Brown v. Board.

00:22:06.852 --> 00:22:08.060
So there's another dimension.

00:22:08.060 --> 00:22:11.340
If the populace were focused on
the problem of corporate power,

00:22:11.340 --> 00:22:12.670
this is something more subtle.

00:22:12.670 --> 00:22:15.300
It's sort of the accumulation
of background rules

00:22:15.300 --> 00:22:18.450
of the game that changed
the way the city functions

00:22:18.450 --> 00:22:20.490
or changed the way
markets function, that

00:22:20.490 --> 00:22:23.250
restrict well-being
and opportunity to some

00:22:23.250 --> 00:22:27.990
and create levels of economic
membership for others.

00:22:27.990 --> 00:22:31.200
A third example, and then
step back for a moment.

00:22:31.200 --> 00:22:33.792
The Flint water crisis in
Michigan, which actually is not

00:22:33.792 --> 00:22:34.500
just about Flint.

00:22:34.500 --> 00:22:36.690
They're actually
hundreds of cities

00:22:36.690 --> 00:22:39.150
that face a similar
configuration

00:22:39.150 --> 00:22:44.700
of lead poisoning,
decaying infrastructure,

00:22:44.700 --> 00:22:47.040
with disproportionate impacts
on communities of color

00:22:47.040 --> 00:22:49.352
and low income communities.

00:22:49.352 --> 00:22:51.060
If you think about
what's going on there,

00:22:51.060 --> 00:22:54.480
here you have a basic
necessity, water--

00:22:54.480 --> 00:22:56.970
the most basic thing
that we need to live--

00:22:56.970 --> 00:22:59.100
that is actually
governed by a mix

00:22:59.100 --> 00:23:02.310
of failing government
actors and increasingly

00:23:02.310 --> 00:23:03.253
privatized control.

00:23:03.253 --> 00:23:04.920
Many of the water
systems in our country

00:23:04.920 --> 00:23:07.770
have been privatized
and financialized

00:23:07.770 --> 00:23:09.270
and are actually
under the ownership

00:23:09.270 --> 00:23:13.620
of different private equity
firms around the country.

00:23:13.620 --> 00:23:15.810
And you have a
basic good that we

00:23:15.810 --> 00:23:19.080
should be relying on for
basic human well-being that

00:23:19.080 --> 00:23:22.170
has actually been converted into
a form of resource extraction

00:23:22.170 --> 00:23:24.120
for the owners of
the water systems,

00:23:24.120 --> 00:23:27.570
with devastating
impacts on communities.

00:23:27.570 --> 00:23:31.860
And so this is a third
way in which we play out

00:23:31.860 --> 00:23:33.660
the dimensions of
economic citizenship

00:23:33.660 --> 00:23:37.050
over who gets to access
those most basic goods that

00:23:37.050 --> 00:23:39.090
make humans and
communities flourish.

00:23:39.090 --> 00:23:41.970
You can tell the same story
about education, the same story

00:23:41.970 --> 00:23:42.780
about health care.

00:23:42.780 --> 00:23:47.100
These are those basic public
goods that don't just appear.

00:23:47.100 --> 00:23:49.140
They're governed and
provided by a mix

00:23:49.140 --> 00:23:51.510
of private and public actors.

00:23:51.510 --> 00:23:54.000
And the communities that
are able to access them

00:23:54.000 --> 00:23:58.080
fully and freely are a
product of those policies

00:23:58.080 --> 00:23:59.110
and decisions.

00:23:59.110 --> 00:24:02.190
So to pull all of that together,
what I think this sketches out

00:24:02.190 --> 00:24:05.280
is three dimensions of
economic citizenship.

00:24:05.280 --> 00:24:09.180
The first is are we free with
respect to concentrated forms

00:24:09.180 --> 00:24:10.230
of private power?

00:24:10.230 --> 00:24:12.120
So think the monopolies
and the trusts,

00:24:12.120 --> 00:24:15.670
which Professor Teachout might
talk about more in a moment.

00:24:15.670 --> 00:24:19.710
The second is are we free in
context of those background

00:24:19.710 --> 00:24:20.790
rules of the game?

00:24:20.790 --> 00:24:24.240
How we structure our city,
how we structure our markets,

00:24:24.240 --> 00:24:28.380
how we structure our
firms, who is able to

00:24:28.380 --> 00:24:31.950
access opportunity and
wealth and well-being.

00:24:31.950 --> 00:24:34.770
And the third is how
we govern our access

00:24:34.770 --> 00:24:36.050
to basic public goods.

00:24:36.050 --> 00:24:38.730
Health care, education, water.

00:24:38.730 --> 00:24:40.140
All three of these
things I think

00:24:40.140 --> 00:24:42.930
are dimensions of
economic membership.

00:24:42.930 --> 00:24:46.230
And all three of them are
products of law and policy.

00:24:46.230 --> 00:24:47.610
And so what that
means then to me

00:24:47.610 --> 00:24:49.410
is that the fight for
economic citizenship

00:24:49.410 --> 00:24:52.320
is really a fight over
power and governance.

00:24:52.320 --> 00:24:56.100
Who controls these economic
decisions on what terms

00:24:56.100 --> 00:24:59.700
and to what ends.

00:24:59.700 --> 00:25:02.010
So then if that's
the case, then I

00:25:02.010 --> 00:25:04.800
think that gives us a much
broader view of citizenship

00:25:04.800 --> 00:25:07.050
as not just a binary on/off.

00:25:07.050 --> 00:25:09.660
I think what that shows us
is that then citizenship can

00:25:09.660 --> 00:25:13.200
actually be tiered
out as a spectrum.

00:25:13.200 --> 00:25:15.540
So you may be formerly
a legal member

00:25:15.540 --> 00:25:17.760
of the polity, a legal citizen.

00:25:17.760 --> 00:25:21.107
But if you functionally can't
access economic opportunity

00:25:21.107 --> 00:25:23.190
and well-being-- if you
functionally have poisoned

00:25:23.190 --> 00:25:29.610
water, if you functionally are
segregated from the centers

00:25:29.610 --> 00:25:31.800
of the city--

00:25:31.800 --> 00:25:35.370
you're not really in effect
a full member of the polity.

00:25:38.190 --> 00:25:42.420
So the next the next
thing here though then

00:25:42.420 --> 00:25:46.260
is if you think about
citizenship as being tiered,

00:25:46.260 --> 00:25:48.960
this also is not just
a state of being.

00:25:48.960 --> 00:25:53.310
There is a politics here and
a set of deliberate interests

00:25:53.310 --> 00:25:54.020
going on here.

00:25:54.020 --> 00:25:58.530
So when you think about
why these policies exist

00:25:58.530 --> 00:26:01.080
the way they do,
part of what we see

00:26:01.080 --> 00:26:04.290
is the weaponization
of economic policy

00:26:04.290 --> 00:26:08.250
in order to restrict who
gets to be a full citizen.

00:26:08.250 --> 00:26:11.130
So the re-segregation
of our cities

00:26:11.130 --> 00:26:15.210
is in part the result of a
fusion of private interests

00:26:15.210 --> 00:26:19.230
of corporations,
zoning interests,

00:26:19.230 --> 00:26:22.320
coming from New York, the
Citizens United reference.

00:26:22.320 --> 00:26:24.690
Real estate and lobbying
and democracy in New York

00:26:24.690 --> 00:26:27.570
are sort of a pretty
central configuration

00:26:27.570 --> 00:26:31.408
of battles that we're fighting
in New York at the moment.

00:26:31.408 --> 00:26:33.450
But so you have a combination
of corporate power,

00:26:33.450 --> 00:26:38.420
corporate interests, and
ideologies of racial hierarchy.

00:26:38.420 --> 00:26:41.490
There are ways in
which we start to use

00:26:41.490 --> 00:26:44.400
these hidden forms of
economic rules and membership

00:26:44.400 --> 00:26:50.970
to reassert those types of
economic and racial hierarchy.

00:26:50.970 --> 00:26:54.600
So to give another
example, after Brown,

00:26:54.600 --> 00:26:58.110
schools are formally
desegregated.

00:26:58.110 --> 00:26:59.880
But what happens
is then you have

00:26:59.880 --> 00:27:04.770
a series of efforts where
municipalities, suburban cities

00:27:04.770 --> 00:27:07.050
secede from the central core.

00:27:07.050 --> 00:27:09.330
So now the schools are
still technically public,

00:27:09.330 --> 00:27:12.570
but they're only serving the
public that you want to serve.

00:27:12.570 --> 00:27:15.150
You have the privatization
movement kicks into high gear,

00:27:15.150 --> 00:27:18.340
again, pulling resources out
from the formal public schools.

00:27:18.340 --> 00:27:20.910
These are all ways of
manipulating economic rules

00:27:20.910 --> 00:27:25.660
to reassert a tiered notion
of who gets to have access.

00:27:25.660 --> 00:27:30.690
So what then you have is a fight
for citizenship and membership

00:27:30.690 --> 00:27:36.720
and inclusion that is at once
about law and policy and a kind

00:27:36.720 --> 00:27:39.540
of technical policy
questions, but also really

00:27:39.540 --> 00:27:42.510
about those most fundamental
issues of who belongs

00:27:42.510 --> 00:27:45.690
and who gets to be
part of the polity.

00:27:45.690 --> 00:27:48.890
So let me move to the
last set of topics

00:27:48.890 --> 00:27:53.660
and about how we think
about fighting these fights.

00:27:53.660 --> 00:27:58.350
And I think there are
really three aspects here.

00:27:58.350 --> 00:28:01.910
And I think of it as ideas,
institutions, and interests.

00:28:01.910 --> 00:28:04.470
So on all three of
these dimensions,

00:28:04.470 --> 00:28:09.410
there's a battle to be waged
for economic citizenship.

00:28:09.410 --> 00:28:11.840
On the ideas front, I
think the first point here

00:28:11.840 --> 00:28:15.170
is that we need to understand
economic membership

00:28:15.170 --> 00:28:17.970
in these broader terms
of power and inclusion,

00:28:17.970 --> 00:28:21.260
and not just in sort of narrow
terms of wages and income.

00:28:21.260 --> 00:28:24.410
And that connects us to these
long standing traditions

00:28:24.410 --> 00:28:27.500
over economic freedom
and domination

00:28:27.500 --> 00:28:30.350
that go back really
to the founding

00:28:30.350 --> 00:28:35.090
and American political thought,
but in global thought as well.

00:28:35.090 --> 00:28:38.630
On the institution side,
these different dimensions

00:28:38.630 --> 00:28:41.480
of policy making
really I think show

00:28:41.480 --> 00:28:43.310
that we're talking
about a much wider set

00:28:43.310 --> 00:28:45.860
of structural debates.

00:28:45.860 --> 00:28:49.880
It's not just enough to talk
about wages or job training

00:28:49.880 --> 00:28:51.230
or skills building.

00:28:51.230 --> 00:28:55.550
Economic citizenship really has
to be tackling those underlying

00:28:55.550 --> 00:28:57.800
concentrations of corporate
power, those background

00:28:57.800 --> 00:29:00.770
rules of the game, the
way in which we structure

00:29:00.770 --> 00:29:03.920
our access to public goods.

00:29:03.920 --> 00:29:06.020
And then on the
interest side-- so this

00:29:06.020 --> 00:29:09.103
is where I think things
get really sticky.

00:29:09.103 --> 00:29:11.145
Because in a lot of ways,
what we're facing now--

00:29:11.145 --> 00:29:13.550
and Dean Brown-Nagin
started with a reference

00:29:13.550 --> 00:29:17.240
to the hurricane in Puerto Rico.

00:29:17.240 --> 00:29:20.240
In some ways, it's
remarkably clarifying

00:29:20.240 --> 00:29:25.130
to see the way in which the
fusion of racial hierarchy,

00:29:25.130 --> 00:29:27.890
corporate power,
and anti-democracy

00:29:27.890 --> 00:29:34.250
drive a political coalition that
results in the kinds of highly

00:29:34.250 --> 00:29:37.160
unequal forms of citizenship
that we're experiencing

00:29:37.160 --> 00:29:39.200
in American politics right now.

00:29:39.200 --> 00:29:42.290
And so that's a particular
set of political interests

00:29:42.290 --> 00:29:47.540
or ideological interests that
are driving and sustaining

00:29:47.540 --> 00:29:50.483
these types of unequal policies.

00:29:50.483 --> 00:29:51.900
But I'm really
interested in think

00:29:51.900 --> 00:29:54.500
about what are the
kinds of coalitions

00:29:54.500 --> 00:29:57.860
and fusions of
interest and movements

00:29:57.860 --> 00:30:00.680
that can advance a
more inclusive vision

00:30:00.680 --> 00:30:01.820
of economic citizenship?

00:30:01.820 --> 00:30:04.040
So here, I think about moments--

00:30:04.040 --> 00:30:07.430
brief moments, perhaps--
but really important moments

00:30:07.430 --> 00:30:10.780
of multiracial inclusive--

00:30:10.780 --> 00:30:13.220
a different kind
of populism maybe

00:30:13.220 --> 00:30:17.060
where you think about that
moment of reconstruction

00:30:17.060 --> 00:30:19.000
after the Civil
War where you had

00:30:19.000 --> 00:30:21.890
the aspirations for
racial inclusion

00:30:21.890 --> 00:30:24.230
and a transformative
vision of the economy that

00:30:24.230 --> 00:30:27.290
came with that
before it was often

00:30:27.290 --> 00:30:31.172
violently put down in
the switch to Jim Crow.

00:30:31.172 --> 00:30:33.380
Or you think about the ways
in which the civil rights

00:30:33.380 --> 00:30:36.080
movement encompassed
an expansive vision

00:30:36.080 --> 00:30:37.670
of economic citizenship as well.

00:30:37.670 --> 00:30:40.010
So the welfare rights
movement following

00:30:40.010 --> 00:30:41.610
after the civil rights movement.

00:30:41.610 --> 00:30:44.450
That's where you start to
see some of the early debates

00:30:44.450 --> 00:30:48.290
around things like basic income
as wages for citizenship.

00:30:48.290 --> 00:30:52.220
But it's coming from a
movement led by women of color

00:30:52.220 --> 00:30:54.530
and not Silicon Valley folks.

00:30:54.530 --> 00:30:57.540
It's a very different
approach to the issue.

00:30:57.540 --> 00:31:01.820
So we have these moments of
multiracial inclusive populist

00:31:01.820 --> 00:31:02.330
movements.

00:31:02.330 --> 00:31:04.850
And I think I would argue
we're in the beginnings of one

00:31:04.850 --> 00:31:05.720
such moment now.

00:31:05.720 --> 00:31:09.800
And so where I'll close is
maybe a question for all of us

00:31:09.800 --> 00:31:12.710
to ponder.

00:31:12.710 --> 00:31:18.320
In this moment of unsettledness
for economic citizenship,

00:31:18.320 --> 00:31:20.270
what are the kinds
of openings that we

00:31:20.270 --> 00:31:24.200
see for new coalitions,
new social movements that

00:31:24.200 --> 00:31:27.170
are advancing this more
transformative, inclusive,

00:31:27.170 --> 00:31:30.620
and structural vision for
economic reform that gets us

00:31:30.620 --> 00:31:33.650
to a more settled, but
also more inclusive

00:31:33.650 --> 00:31:35.480
understanding of
economic citizenship?

00:31:35.480 --> 00:31:37.123
So I'll close there.

00:31:37.123 --> 00:31:37.623
Thank you.

