00:33:36.190 --> 00:33:39.370
Alaska Natives maintain
dual citizenship

00:33:39.370 --> 00:33:43.690
as American citizens and
of their respective tribes.

00:33:43.690 --> 00:33:46.210
They are similar to other
Native Americans who

00:33:46.210 --> 00:33:49.180
are members of federally
recognized tribes,

00:33:49.180 --> 00:33:52.210
but they differ in
one dramatic way.

00:33:52.210 --> 00:33:57.910
They are also members of Alaska
Native tribal corporations.

00:33:57.910 --> 00:34:00.820
Alaska Natives settle their
aboriginal land claims

00:34:00.820 --> 00:34:06.420
through the Alaska Native
Claims Settlement Act of 1971.

00:34:06.420 --> 00:34:09.820
And ANCSA created 13
regional corporations

00:34:09.820 --> 00:34:13.750
and 200 plus village
native corporations

00:34:13.750 --> 00:34:17.469
to implement the
claims, thus making

00:34:17.469 --> 00:34:22.350
Alaska native shareholders
in these corporations.

00:34:22.350 --> 00:34:25.770
Alaska Natives sought full
control over their lands

00:34:25.770 --> 00:34:28.920
rather than allowing the
federal government to have

00:34:28.920 --> 00:34:31.510
oversight over their lands.

00:34:31.510 --> 00:34:34.139
They rejected the
reservation systems

00:34:34.139 --> 00:34:37.110
that are held in trust
by the federal government

00:34:37.110 --> 00:34:41.190
for federally recognized
tribes and instead supported

00:34:41.190 --> 00:34:44.460
conveyance of lands held
under fee-simple title

00:34:44.460 --> 00:34:47.300
by corporations.

00:34:47.300 --> 00:34:51.489
ANCSA corporations differ
from other profit making

00:34:51.489 --> 00:34:54.520
corporations in many respects.

00:34:54.520 --> 00:34:56.980
They are federally
recognized tribes

00:34:56.980 --> 00:35:01.480
for special statutory
purposes in over 100

00:35:01.480 --> 00:35:03.880
federal legislative acts.

00:35:03.880 --> 00:35:07.060
They do not, however,
have sovereign immunity

00:35:07.060 --> 00:35:11.170
or governance authorities that
are prerogatives of tribes.

00:35:11.170 --> 00:35:13.750
They also have social
and cultural dimensions

00:35:13.750 --> 00:35:19.330
and responsibilities as well
as the profit making objective.

00:35:19.330 --> 00:35:22.210
In addition, they also
have a unique form

00:35:22.210 --> 00:35:27.370
of corporate socialism in that
regional agencies are required

00:35:27.370 --> 00:35:32.860
to share 70% of their profits
from subsurface and timber

00:35:32.860 --> 00:35:35.020
development among themselves.

00:35:35.020 --> 00:35:38.320
To date, more than
$300 million has been

00:35:38.320 --> 00:35:42.860
shared among the regional ANCs.

00:35:42.860 --> 00:35:45.260
Native American tribes
outside of Alaska

00:35:45.260 --> 00:35:49.280
have full responsibilities for
the welfare of their members.

00:35:49.280 --> 00:35:54.530
In Alaska, governmental
responsibilities, services,

00:35:54.530 --> 00:35:59.180
and benefits are dispersed
among tribes, ANCs,

00:35:59.180 --> 00:36:01.860
and several other institutions.

00:36:01.860 --> 00:36:05.720
We have 10 regional non-profit
tribal organizations

00:36:05.720 --> 00:36:09.020
and two regionally
federally recognized tribes

00:36:09.020 --> 00:36:12.170
that provide a range of
governmental services.

00:36:12.170 --> 00:36:17.270
We have one statewide and 12
regional health organizations.

00:36:17.270 --> 00:36:21.650
And we have 12 regional
housing authorities.

00:36:21.650 --> 00:36:25.580
These organizations and tribes
are dependent on federal funds

00:36:25.580 --> 00:36:28.550
to provide the
governmental services.

00:36:28.550 --> 00:36:31.940
And as such, they are
required to comply

00:36:31.940 --> 00:36:34.700
with government
eligibility requirements

00:36:34.700 --> 00:36:36.890
to receive benefits.

00:36:36.890 --> 00:36:40.250
Recipients must demonstrate
that they are enrolled members

00:36:40.250 --> 00:36:43.640
of tribes and have a
certificate of degree

00:36:43.640 --> 00:36:48.050
of Indian blood demonstrating
that they meet the blood

00:36:48.050 --> 00:36:50.750
quantum eligibility
requirements that

00:36:50.750 --> 00:36:55.640
is most often set at the one
fourth native blood quantum.

00:36:55.640 --> 00:36:59.090
While discussions of the rights
and responsibilities of tribes

00:36:59.090 --> 00:37:02.660
and ANCs are worthy,
this discussion

00:37:02.660 --> 00:37:05.630
here provides a
historical review

00:37:05.630 --> 00:37:08.540
of native membership
and citizenships,

00:37:08.540 --> 00:37:11.720
which are not synonymous.

00:37:11.720 --> 00:37:16.160
In our own traditional society,
we have clans and family units,

00:37:16.160 --> 00:37:18.800
and we have tribes and nations.

00:37:18.800 --> 00:37:22.400
And in these entities, we
have perpetual memberships

00:37:22.400 --> 00:37:25.430
in our tribes and in our clans.

00:37:25.430 --> 00:37:28.130
In 1867, we had the
Treaty of Session,

00:37:28.130 --> 00:37:33.380
under which Alaska was sold
by Russia to United States.

00:37:33.380 --> 00:37:36.980
And Alaska Natives
were classified

00:37:36.980 --> 00:37:40.380
as uncivilized tribes.

00:37:40.380 --> 00:37:42.360
Then we have the
General Allotment Act

00:37:42.360 --> 00:37:45.930
that applied to both Native
Americans and Alaska Natives.

00:37:45.930 --> 00:37:51.300
And we have the blood quantum
system that was introduced.

00:37:51.300 --> 00:37:55.680
This act supposedly
was to civilize Indians

00:37:55.680 --> 00:37:58.980
by introducing them
to private property.

00:37:58.980 --> 00:38:03.450
Tribal lands were
divided into 160 acres,

00:38:03.450 --> 00:38:09.210
and surplus lands
totalling 90 million acres

00:38:09.210 --> 00:38:14.270
were transferred into the
public, leaving Indian hands.

00:38:14.270 --> 00:38:16.200
The other interesting
thing about it

00:38:16.200 --> 00:38:18.060
was that the Bureau
of Indian Affairs

00:38:18.060 --> 00:38:20.430
introduced a
competency, or what I

00:38:20.430 --> 00:38:23.910
think is an assimilationist
measurement.

00:38:23.910 --> 00:38:28.140
Those Native Americans who
were less than 50% native blood

00:38:28.140 --> 00:38:31.590
didn't have to have
any BIA supervision.

00:38:31.590 --> 00:38:34.260
They were viewed as assimilated.

00:38:34.260 --> 00:38:38.070
Those who were 50%
or more native blood

00:38:38.070 --> 00:38:41.310
had to have BIA supervision.

00:38:44.170 --> 00:38:46.410
It was possible to
obtain citizenship

00:38:46.410 --> 00:38:49.590
if they severed tribal
relations and adopted

00:38:49.590 --> 00:38:51.780
habits of civilizations.

00:38:51.780 --> 00:38:54.810
Not too many became citizens.

00:38:54.810 --> 00:39:00.210
In Alaska, we adopted a
Territorial Act of 1915.

00:39:00.210 --> 00:39:04.830
And under this, Alaska natives
could achieve citizenship

00:39:04.830 --> 00:39:08.700
if they could pass a test
demonstrating qualifications

00:39:08.700 --> 00:39:12.630
to exercise the
obligations of a voter.

00:39:12.630 --> 00:39:15.240
They also had to
abandon tribal customs

00:39:15.240 --> 00:39:17.670
and sever tribal relations.

00:39:17.670 --> 00:39:21.300
They also had to adopt the
habits of civilizations.

00:39:21.300 --> 00:39:24.930
And they had to be certified
by five white citizens.

00:39:24.930 --> 00:39:26.550
And then after all
of that, they had

00:39:26.550 --> 00:39:31.110
to solemnly swear to forever
renounce all tribal customs

00:39:31.110 --> 00:39:32.820
and relationships.

00:39:32.820 --> 00:39:35.880
Again, we had very few
that became citizens.

00:39:35.880 --> 00:39:38.510
Except for one,
Charlie Jones, who

00:39:38.510 --> 00:39:41.400
was a clan leader
from Wrangell area.

00:39:41.400 --> 00:39:43.680
And he had been voting
for a number years

00:39:43.680 --> 00:39:48.120
and then went to the
polls to vote in 1922.

00:39:48.120 --> 00:39:50.580
And he was not allowed to vote.

00:39:50.580 --> 00:39:53.790
He called on his
niece, who called

00:39:53.790 --> 00:39:57.780
on her father, William L.
Paul, the first Tlingit lawyer

00:39:57.780 --> 00:39:59.400
in Alaska.

00:39:59.400 --> 00:40:04.860
They litigated it, and Charlie
Jones got the right to vote,

00:40:04.860 --> 00:40:10.410
thereby giving de facto
citizenship to Alaska natives.

00:40:10.410 --> 00:40:13.530
In 1924, we have
the Citizenship Act

00:40:13.530 --> 00:40:17.790
that gives citizenships to all
Native Americans and Alaska

00:40:17.790 --> 00:40:19.380
Natives.

00:40:19.380 --> 00:40:24.150
We have then the Indian
Reorganization Act of 1934

00:40:24.150 --> 00:40:27.420
that authorizes native
governments and constitutions,

00:40:27.420 --> 00:40:30.300
but it didn't extend to Alaska.

00:40:30.300 --> 00:40:35.370
So we went to Congress
to amend the IRA in 1936

00:40:35.370 --> 00:40:38.410
to extend to Alaska.

00:40:38.410 --> 00:40:43.570
We now have 229 federally
recognized tribes,

00:40:43.570 --> 00:40:47.410
but they are sovereigns
without a territorial reach.

00:40:47.410 --> 00:40:50.380
And you also have to be
one fourth native blood

00:40:50.380 --> 00:40:54.300
quantum to be a tribal member.

00:40:54.300 --> 00:41:00.510
In 1971, we enacted the Alaska
Native Claims Settlement Act.

00:41:00.510 --> 00:41:04.410
And under this act, our
aboriginal land claims

00:41:04.410 --> 00:41:05.490
were settled.

00:41:05.490 --> 00:41:10.170
The act established 13
regional corporations and 200

00:41:10.170 --> 00:41:12.780
plus village corporations.

00:41:12.780 --> 00:41:16.290
Our land-- we received
44 million acres

00:41:16.290 --> 00:41:19.200
under fee-simple title.

00:41:19.200 --> 00:41:24.120
We were given $1 billion
for the extinguishment

00:41:24.120 --> 00:41:29.310
of our aboriginal title
to 330 million acres.

00:41:29.310 --> 00:41:34.010
$1 billion for
330 million acres.

00:41:34.010 --> 00:41:37.500
A very resource rich land.

00:41:37.500 --> 00:41:40.320
But the act also established
that one fourth native blood

00:41:40.320 --> 00:41:42.810
quantum for memberships.

00:41:42.810 --> 00:41:44.970
But the act also did
something very different

00:41:44.970 --> 00:41:51.150
here in it created a new ethnic
group called Alaska Natives.

00:41:51.150 --> 00:41:57.300
Under this, we were able to
pull our blood quantum from all

00:41:57.300 --> 00:42:00.270
of the different cultural
groups, the IÃ±upiat, Yupik,

00:42:00.270 --> 00:42:04.890
Aleut, Athabaskan, Tlingit,
Haida, and Tsimshians.

00:42:04.890 --> 00:42:09.900
I just wanted to introduce
you to the Marine Mammal Act.

00:42:09.900 --> 00:42:15.390
This act provides an exemption
to hunt marine mammals

00:42:15.390 --> 00:42:18.430
for Alaska Natives who could
prove that they are one

00:42:18.430 --> 00:42:21.390
fourth native blood quantum.

00:42:21.390 --> 00:42:23.820
In the 1980s, we
began to realize

00:42:23.820 --> 00:42:27.630
that there were some
restrictions in ANCSA itself

00:42:27.630 --> 00:42:30.220
that conflicted with
our cultural values.

00:42:30.220 --> 00:42:33.060
So we went to Congress
to seek an amendment.

00:42:33.060 --> 00:42:36.000
And one of those
amendments allowed

00:42:36.000 --> 00:42:41.520
us to enroll natives who
were born after 1971.

00:42:41.520 --> 00:42:43.890
The original act
allowed only for those

00:42:43.890 --> 00:42:47.220
who were alive in 1971
to become shareholders.

00:42:47.220 --> 00:42:52.260
We realized that our lands
were owned by our children--

00:42:52.260 --> 00:42:53.970
it was their right
to own our lands.

00:42:53.970 --> 00:42:58.770
And so we wanted to make
sure that we could do that.

00:42:58.770 --> 00:43:00.600
We had a big debate in Congress.

00:43:00.600 --> 00:43:02.960
Our secretary of interior
didn't want us to do that.

00:43:02.960 --> 00:43:04.980
He wanted to assimilate us.

00:43:04.980 --> 00:43:09.720
And we prevailed and
got the authorization.

00:43:09.720 --> 00:43:14.010
But we wanted the act to
give automatic enrollment

00:43:14.010 --> 00:43:15.600
to all of our children.

00:43:15.600 --> 00:43:19.710
But the compromise was that
we had to have a shareholder

00:43:19.710 --> 00:43:24.150
resolution, and it required
a super majority shareholder

00:43:24.150 --> 00:43:24.690
vote.

00:43:24.690 --> 00:43:27.480
That means you had
to have 50% plus one

00:43:27.480 --> 00:43:30.570
of all outstanding
shares to vote in favor

00:43:30.570 --> 00:43:35.190
of enrolling new members.

00:43:35.190 --> 00:43:38.340
To date, we have six
regional corporations

00:43:38.340 --> 00:43:43.260
that have voted to allow
the enrollment of children

00:43:43.260 --> 00:43:46.350
who are born after 1971.

00:43:46.350 --> 00:43:50.790
We have four corporations that
adopted the one fourth blood

00:43:50.790 --> 00:43:54.240
quantum; Ahtna, Doyon,
NANA, and Sealaska.

00:43:54.240 --> 00:43:56.820
I chaired the committee that
oversaw that enrollment.

00:43:56.820 --> 00:44:00.060
And I will tell
you, I did surveys,

00:44:00.060 --> 00:44:03.930
I did look at the
demographics, projections.

00:44:03.930 --> 00:44:06.480
And I also did focus groups.

00:44:06.480 --> 00:44:10.230
And it was really clear
to me that it was possible

00:44:10.230 --> 00:44:16.650
that we would not be able
to pass that resolution if I

00:44:16.650 --> 00:44:18.960
went with anything
less than one eighth.

00:44:18.960 --> 00:44:20.790
So we went with the one eighth.

00:44:20.790 --> 00:44:24.270
And as the vote was coming
in, I was really terrified

00:44:24.270 --> 00:44:27.420
because the inspector
of elections

00:44:27.420 --> 00:44:31.170
called me late at night and
said, Rosita, we're losing.

00:44:31.170 --> 00:44:33.660
And I was just devastated.

00:44:33.660 --> 00:44:36.300
And then he called me back
about a couple hours later

00:44:36.300 --> 00:44:38.520
and said that he
had made a mistake

00:44:38.520 --> 00:44:39.870
and that we were winning.

00:44:39.870 --> 00:44:41.880
[LAUGHTER]

00:44:41.880 --> 00:44:45.480
So we have another corporation.

00:44:45.480 --> 00:44:48.540
The Arctic Slope has
two types of stock.

00:44:48.540 --> 00:44:52.830
And one type goes to
those who are one fourth,

00:44:52.830 --> 00:44:56.700
and then the other is to those
who have the less than one

00:44:56.700 --> 00:44:58.930
fourth native blood.

00:44:58.930 --> 00:45:02.580
Only Calista, the
corporation that

00:45:02.580 --> 00:45:07.590
has probably still
the most native blood,

00:45:07.590 --> 00:45:10.530
but went with
lineal descendants.

00:45:10.530 --> 00:45:14.610
So we make a distinction
between membership rights

00:45:14.610 --> 00:45:16.290
and citizenship rights.

00:45:16.290 --> 00:45:19.410
Our membership rights are
based on the descendancy

00:45:19.410 --> 00:45:24.060
from an enrolled tribal member
or shareholder and blood

00:45:24.060 --> 00:45:28.050
quantum criteria as defined
in tribal constitutions

00:45:28.050 --> 00:45:30.420
or corporate bylaws.

00:45:30.420 --> 00:45:34.910
It establishes our eligibility
for benefits, dividends, health

00:45:34.910 --> 00:45:37.530
care, housing, scholarships.

00:45:37.530 --> 00:45:42.120
And then we have citizenship,
tribal citizenship.

00:45:42.120 --> 00:45:45.570
Tribal citizens' rights
and responsibilities

00:45:45.570 --> 00:45:49.410
are related to the exercise
of tribal sovereign rights

00:45:49.410 --> 00:45:52.710
and are similar to
that of US citizens.

00:45:52.710 --> 00:45:57.180
Memberships in ANCs does not
confer tribal citizenship

00:45:57.180 --> 00:46:00.000
rights, although shareholders
do have the right

00:46:00.000 --> 00:46:06.480
to serve and elect leaders
of a board of directors.

00:46:06.480 --> 00:46:11.280
And they have the right to vote
for other businesses that may

00:46:11.280 --> 00:46:13.830
come before the corporation.

00:46:13.830 --> 00:46:16.920
I wanted you to take a
look at the blood quantum

00:46:16.920 --> 00:46:19.860
as it exists right now.

00:46:19.860 --> 00:46:24.120
I don't have any data on Alaska
Natives who are less than one

00:46:24.120 --> 00:46:25.570
fourth the total number.

00:46:25.570 --> 00:46:28.170
But what I thought I
would do is take a look

00:46:28.170 --> 00:46:34.770
at native people who applied for
their CDIB, their certificate

00:46:34.770 --> 00:46:42.000
of Indian blood, in a 10 year
period from 2006 to 2016.

00:46:42.000 --> 00:46:46.920
We see that Cook Inlet, 59.3%
of them who are enrolled

00:46:46.920 --> 00:46:48.810
were less than one fourth.

00:46:48.810 --> 00:46:51.470
And it goes down.

00:46:51.470 --> 00:46:55.560
The highest are those in the
southern coastal regions.

00:46:55.560 --> 00:46:59.280
And you see my region at 32%.

00:46:59.280 --> 00:47:02.610
Even though we were
introduced to Western society

00:47:02.610 --> 00:47:04.770
and had contact
with Western society

00:47:04.770 --> 00:47:10.240
much earlier than others,
we still are at the 32%.

00:47:10.240 --> 00:47:13.530
It's still problematic for
us, discouraging for us.

00:47:13.530 --> 00:47:16.140
And then you see
Calista at the bottom,

00:47:16.140 --> 00:47:18.360
and they're in
southwestern Alaska.

00:47:18.360 --> 00:47:22.960
And 7.5% of them were
less than the one

00:47:22.960 --> 00:47:26.820
fourth when they enrolled
in that 10 year period.

00:47:26.820 --> 00:47:30.090
This table does not reflect the
total number of Alaska Natives

00:47:30.090 --> 00:47:33.510
within each region who are less
than one fourth native blood

00:47:33.510 --> 00:47:34.350
quantum.

00:47:34.350 --> 00:47:37.050
We don't have any
current data that

00:47:37.050 --> 00:47:40.200
exists of the percentages
of Alaska Natives who

00:47:40.200 --> 00:47:43.080
are less than the one
fourth native blood quantum.

00:47:43.080 --> 00:47:46.950
However, a recent study by
Sealaska Heritage Institutes

00:47:46.950 --> 00:47:49.140
demonstrates from
both qualitative

00:47:49.140 --> 00:47:52.830
and quantitative data that an
increasing number of Alaska

00:47:52.830 --> 00:47:55.440
Natives are less than the
one fourth native blood,

00:47:55.440 --> 00:48:00.210
and particularly those in
the southern coastal regions.

00:48:00.210 --> 00:48:04.140
Tribes and ANCs in
Alaska allow natives

00:48:04.140 --> 00:48:06.690
to combine their native
blood from parents

00:48:06.690 --> 00:48:09.540
who may be from different
tribes, cultural groups,

00:48:09.540 --> 00:48:13.320
or ANCs to meet the one
fourth native blood quantum

00:48:13.320 --> 00:48:15.540
eligibility requirement.

00:48:15.540 --> 00:48:18.720
The ability to combine
blood quantum offsets

00:48:18.720 --> 00:48:22.800
the dilemma faced by some Native
Americans whose parents are

00:48:22.800 --> 00:48:24.750
members of different tribes.

00:48:24.750 --> 00:48:28.470
The offspring may be full
blooded Native American,

00:48:28.470 --> 00:48:31.770
but not meet the blood
quantum requirement of either

00:48:31.770 --> 00:48:33.420
of their parents tribes.

00:48:33.420 --> 00:48:36.690
And thus, are not eligible
for tribal membership

00:48:36.690 --> 00:48:39.240
in either parents' tribes.

00:48:39.240 --> 00:48:42.240
The ability to combine blood
quantum of different Alaska

00:48:42.240 --> 00:48:44.670
Native cultural groups
and corporations

00:48:44.670 --> 00:48:48.780
may delay an overall
decreasing native blood quantum

00:48:48.780 --> 00:48:51.300
for an undetermined period.

00:48:51.300 --> 00:48:53.910
But we know it's coming.

00:48:53.910 --> 00:48:55.860
The issue of blood
quantum has also

00:48:55.860 --> 00:48:57.600
become quite controversial.

00:48:57.600 --> 00:48:59.670
I mentioned to you
the Marine Mammal Act.

00:48:59.670 --> 00:49:03.060
The Marine Mammal Act allows for
an exemption for Alaska Natives

00:49:03.060 --> 00:49:06.990
to hunt marine mammals.

00:49:06.990 --> 00:49:11.290
We've been hunting them for
over 1,000 years or more.

00:49:11.290 --> 00:49:14.490
And we use the byproducts for
traditional arts and crafts,

00:49:14.490 --> 00:49:16.440
which are really
important for us

00:49:16.440 --> 00:49:21.000
in our economically
depressed rural communities.

00:49:21.000 --> 00:49:25.710
Unfortunately, it has the
one fourth blood quantum

00:49:25.710 --> 00:49:26.790
requirement.

00:49:26.790 --> 00:49:29.040
And it's in those
southern coastal regions

00:49:29.040 --> 00:49:34.200
that are affected the
most by this requirement.

00:49:34.200 --> 00:49:35.820
We have been trying
to amend this,

00:49:35.820 --> 00:49:37.200
but we can't come
to an agreement

00:49:37.200 --> 00:49:40.010
in the native
community as of yet.

00:49:40.010 --> 00:49:43.710
A continued relationship
to the ancestral lands

00:49:43.710 --> 00:49:46.380
continues to be a
significant cultural value

00:49:46.380 --> 00:49:48.000
for Alaska Natives.

00:49:48.000 --> 00:49:51.240
Native tribes do not
have a land base.

00:49:51.240 --> 00:49:53.520
Instead, it's the
native corporations

00:49:53.520 --> 00:49:55.830
that own our ancestral lands.

00:49:55.830 --> 00:50:00.720
Thus, membership in ANCs
and continued land ownership

00:50:00.720 --> 00:50:03.690
are significant
for Alaska Natives.

00:50:03.690 --> 00:50:07.770
The blood quantum system is
a major Alaska native issue

00:50:07.770 --> 00:50:11.790
since it defines membership in
tribes and native corporations

00:50:11.790 --> 00:50:15.090
as well as eligibility
for federal services.

00:50:15.090 --> 00:50:19.170
Most all of Alaska natives
were organized under the IRA

00:50:19.170 --> 00:50:22.320
and use the one fourth
native blood quantum criteria

00:50:22.320 --> 00:50:23.760
for membership.

00:50:23.760 --> 00:50:28.740
All ANCs with the exception
of one regional corporation

00:50:28.740 --> 00:50:32.100
uses the one fourth native
blood quantum criteria

00:50:32.100 --> 00:50:35.670
to determine
membership eligibility.

00:50:35.670 --> 00:50:39.030
The existing data suggests
that if the blood quantum

00:50:39.030 --> 00:50:42.780
system continues to be utilized
to determine membership,

00:50:42.780 --> 00:50:47.250
tribes may well be on
a path to extinction.

00:50:47.250 --> 00:50:49.380
An increasing number
of Alaska natives

00:50:49.380 --> 00:50:52.710
who are one fourth
and less native blood

00:50:52.710 --> 00:50:55.140
means that native
corporations will

00:50:55.140 --> 00:50:57.450
be owned by
shareholders who will

00:50:57.450 --> 00:51:01.920
be predominantly less than
the one fourth native blood.

00:51:01.920 --> 00:51:04.650
The greater fear is
that these shareholders

00:51:04.650 --> 00:51:08.880
may not have the same cultural
values of land ownership

00:51:08.880 --> 00:51:11.610
and may be more
than likely inclined

00:51:11.610 --> 00:51:15.210
to lift the restrictions
on the sale of land.

00:51:15.210 --> 00:51:20.520
In fact, some of our CEOs have
called our land wasting assets.

00:51:20.520 --> 00:51:22.975
I might note that those
are non-native CEOs.

00:51:27.180 --> 00:51:31.770
I wanted to show you my
grandfather's citizenship

00:51:31.770 --> 00:51:33.030
certificate.

00:51:33.030 --> 00:51:35.700
My grandfather, John M. Tlunaut.

00:51:35.700 --> 00:51:41.610
He was required to renounce
his tribal relations.

00:51:41.610 --> 00:51:45.810
He had to swear that he
wasn't going to affiliate

00:51:45.810 --> 00:51:48.420
with his tribal relatives.

00:51:48.420 --> 00:51:51.540
And he had to go before
five teachers who

00:51:51.540 --> 00:51:56.250
approved his knowledge that
he knew about citizenship

00:51:56.250 --> 00:51:59.730
and all the responsibilities
of citizenship.

00:51:59.730 --> 00:52:05.070
And then he had to have
five white people sign

00:52:05.070 --> 00:52:08.810
that he was, indeed, a
civilized Alaska Native.

00:52:11.440 --> 00:52:12.760
He was later pressured--

00:52:12.760 --> 00:52:14.230
I thought this was interesting.

00:52:14.230 --> 00:52:16.060
He was later pressured
by missionaries

00:52:16.060 --> 00:52:20.950
to change his name from Marx.

00:52:20.950 --> 00:52:26.590
It used to be M-A-R-X. He was
persuaded to change it to Mark

00:52:26.590 --> 00:52:29.635
when this name became
unpopular in the United States.

00:52:29.635 --> 00:52:31.540
[LAUGHTER]

00:52:31.540 --> 00:52:34.300
Ironically, I,
his granddaughter,

00:52:34.300 --> 00:52:38.320
now serve as president of the
Sealaska Heritage Institute,

00:52:38.320 --> 00:52:42.730
whose mission is to perpetuate
and enhance the Tlingit, Haida,

00:52:42.730 --> 00:52:46.390
and Tsimshian cultures
of Southeast Alaska.

00:52:46.390 --> 00:52:47.675
[NON-ENGLISH SPEECH]

00:52:47.675 --> 00:52:51.555
[APPLAUSE]

00:52:58.350 --> 00:53:01.020
- Next, we have Zephyr Teachout.

00:53:01.020 --> 00:53:01.920
- Thank you.

00:53:01.920 --> 00:53:02.940
That was fascinating.

00:53:02.940 --> 00:53:04.240
Great presentations.

00:53:04.240 --> 00:53:06.600
Well, you just heard
about how governments

00:53:06.600 --> 00:53:08.610
can be corporations.

00:53:08.610 --> 00:53:10.980
I want to talk about
the ways in which--

00:53:10.980 --> 00:53:14.880
following up on a previous
conversation-- corporations

00:53:14.880 --> 00:53:16.590
can play a governmental role.

00:53:16.590 --> 00:53:18.900
And I think one of things
we're all suggesting

00:53:18.900 --> 00:53:22.140
is that we have to shed our
formal understanding of what

00:53:22.140 --> 00:53:26.400
government and citizenship is
and look at the deep functions

00:53:26.400 --> 00:53:28.810
of what's happening.

00:53:28.810 --> 00:53:32.730
I'm going to spend some time
talking about contract farming.

00:53:32.730 --> 00:53:34.380
Hopefully terrify
you into seeing

00:53:34.380 --> 00:53:36.180
that that's the future
of work and that

00:53:36.180 --> 00:53:39.600
radically changes the
relationship of people

00:53:39.600 --> 00:53:41.710
to power.

00:53:41.710 --> 00:53:44.940
But first, I just want to
use one of the oldest or one

00:53:44.940 --> 00:53:49.290
of the more terrifying
examples of corporations

00:53:49.290 --> 00:53:52.795
by access to a choke point
playing a governing rule.

00:53:52.795 --> 00:53:54.170
And this is the
credit monopolies

00:53:54.170 --> 00:53:56.245
in the late 19th century.

00:53:56.245 --> 00:54:00.930
So late 19th century,
credit monopolies in regions

00:54:00.930 --> 00:54:04.320
controlled all access to credit.

00:54:04.320 --> 00:54:10.770
So that meant that freed slaves
looking for credit with which

00:54:10.770 --> 00:54:13.650
to be able to rent
land had to go

00:54:13.650 --> 00:54:18.300
to a local store owner, who also
had the only access to credit.

00:54:18.300 --> 00:54:20.887
And the local store owner
charged totally usurious rates.

00:54:20.887 --> 00:54:23.220
And it's quite clear they
charged more than they should.

00:54:23.220 --> 00:54:27.180
So we might stop there and say
this is on its face unfair.

00:54:27.180 --> 00:54:29.040
But it was more than the rates.

00:54:29.040 --> 00:54:32.790
It was actually a governing
relationship because the credit

00:54:32.790 --> 00:54:34.560
monopolist would
say, I'm only going

00:54:34.560 --> 00:54:38.250
to lend to you if
you shop at my store

00:54:38.250 --> 00:54:42.150
because I also provide
all the dry goods.

00:54:42.150 --> 00:54:44.910
That effectively shut
out any competitors

00:54:44.910 --> 00:54:47.970
who might come in and
land at a lower level.

00:54:47.970 --> 00:54:49.970
Because if they
came in, nobody was

00:54:49.970 --> 00:54:51.720
going to shop at their
store because you'd

00:54:51.720 --> 00:54:54.630
lose the excess to credit.

00:54:54.630 --> 00:55:01.270
But they also said you can
only plant cotton, even

00:55:01.270 --> 00:55:06.640
in cases where cotton was
not the most profitable crop.

00:55:06.640 --> 00:55:11.230
Because cotton was not a product
that the farmers could then

00:55:11.230 --> 00:55:15.610
use to build
self-sufficiency and get out

00:55:15.610 --> 00:55:19.540
of their relationship
with a credit monopolist.

00:55:19.540 --> 00:55:21.640
It had to be shipped north.

00:55:21.640 --> 00:55:24.820
They couldn't basically
cultivate the land in ways

00:55:24.820 --> 00:55:28.780
to escape this
governing relationship.

00:55:28.780 --> 00:55:30.730
So farming is often--

00:55:30.730 --> 00:55:34.937
and in fact, without the boll
weevil and other changes,

00:55:34.937 --> 00:55:36.520
it might have gone
on for even longer.

00:55:36.520 --> 00:55:39.190
But this was an
effective central role

00:55:39.190 --> 00:55:41.260
in the suppression
of citizenship

00:55:41.260 --> 00:55:45.250
for African-Americans
for over 40 years

00:55:45.250 --> 00:55:48.640
is the choke point of
the credit monopolists.

00:55:48.640 --> 00:55:52.690
So farming is often both
an example in itself

00:55:52.690 --> 00:55:55.180
terrifying, but also
an example of what else

00:55:55.180 --> 00:55:56.540
is happening in a society.

00:55:56.540 --> 00:55:59.860
So I think we should always
look to farming to see-- look

00:55:59.860 --> 00:56:01.818
at the nature of work.

00:56:01.818 --> 00:56:03.610
So I'm going to spend
a few minutes talking

00:56:03.610 --> 00:56:05.070
about contract farming.

00:56:08.470 --> 00:56:12.760
If you are a chicken
farmer, you basically

00:56:12.760 --> 00:56:18.130
have to find a way to get
your chicken to market, right?

00:56:18.130 --> 00:56:25.300
So right now, in the United
States, 95% of chicken farmers

00:56:25.300 --> 00:56:26.860
are basically stuck
in a system where

00:56:26.860 --> 00:56:29.320
the only way they can get
their chicken to market

00:56:29.320 --> 00:56:33.490
is they go through Perdue,
Pilgrims, or Tyson.

00:56:33.490 --> 00:56:35.290
And if they don't go
through those three,

00:56:35.290 --> 00:56:37.810
they just can't get
their chickens to market.

00:56:37.810 --> 00:56:39.730
So this sounds OK, right?

00:56:39.730 --> 00:56:41.650
But these choke points--

00:56:41.650 --> 00:56:45.580
Tyson, Perdue, Pilgrims-- play
this governing relationship

00:56:45.580 --> 00:56:46.690
to the chicken farmer.

00:56:46.690 --> 00:56:52.145
They don't just extract
value saying basically

00:56:52.145 --> 00:56:54.770
you have to pay these high fees
to get your chickens to market.

00:56:54.770 --> 00:56:57.220
They also say to
the chicken farmer,

00:56:57.220 --> 00:57:00.320
well, if you want us to
distribute your chickens,

00:57:00.320 --> 00:57:06.730
you are going to have to use the
hatched eggs that we provide.

00:57:06.730 --> 00:57:11.705
You are going to have to
use the exact specification

00:57:11.705 --> 00:57:13.330
of the chicken houses
that we tell you.

00:57:13.330 --> 00:57:15.220
You are going to have
to use our advisors.

00:57:15.220 --> 00:57:16.960
You are going to have to
use our watering system.

00:57:16.960 --> 00:57:19.000
You are going to have to
use our dimming system.

00:57:19.000 --> 00:57:20.583
You are going to
have to use our feed.

00:57:23.320 --> 00:57:25.530
And if you don't, that's fine.

00:57:25.530 --> 00:57:27.350
You are free.

00:57:27.350 --> 00:57:30.290
We just won't take your
chickens to market.

00:57:30.290 --> 00:57:32.900
Now, the chicken farmers have
taken out a loan typically

00:57:32.900 --> 00:57:35.120
around $1 million.

00:57:35.120 --> 00:57:37.290
And so if those chickens
don't go to market,

00:57:37.290 --> 00:57:39.685
they're totally bankrupt.

00:57:39.685 --> 00:57:41.060
So you can see
how, first of all,

00:57:41.060 --> 00:57:43.528
this allows for the
distributor to extract

00:57:43.528 --> 00:57:44.570
enormous amount of value.

00:57:44.570 --> 00:57:47.180
And you may see both Bernie
Sanders and Elizabeth Warren

00:57:47.180 --> 00:57:52.040
talking about how farmers get
$0.20 per dollar or less now

00:57:52.040 --> 00:57:54.890
than they did 30 years ago
for all the food that goes

00:57:54.890 --> 00:57:55.612
to market.

00:57:55.612 --> 00:57:56.570
But it's not just that.

00:57:56.570 --> 00:57:57.950
They also sign
contracts that say

00:57:57.950 --> 00:57:59.367
they can't talk
to their neighbors

00:57:59.367 --> 00:58:02.910
about how much Tyson
is paying them.

00:58:02.910 --> 00:58:07.100
So embedded in the
contract, there

00:58:07.100 --> 00:58:09.980
is isolation, social isolation.

00:58:09.980 --> 00:58:12.770
You can't even talk to
the farmer you hate.

00:58:12.770 --> 00:58:15.290
So when you think of social,
it's not just about solidarity.

00:58:15.290 --> 00:58:17.780
It's about the entire
complicated community that

00:58:17.780 --> 00:58:21.860
comes along with economic life.

00:58:21.860 --> 00:58:25.600
You can't tell how much
you have been paid.

00:58:25.600 --> 00:58:28.940
And if suddenly your chicken
production goes way down,

00:58:28.940 --> 00:58:32.240
you don't know whether
it's because Tyson

00:58:32.240 --> 00:58:35.000
is experimenting on you or not.

00:58:35.000 --> 00:58:39.080
Essentially, they've created
a panopticon-like arrangement.

00:58:39.080 --> 00:58:42.770
You may be familiar with
Bentham's panopticon.

00:58:42.770 --> 00:58:45.170
The jailer sits in
the center and can

00:58:45.170 --> 00:58:48.020
see all the behaviors
of the different people,

00:58:48.020 --> 00:58:51.430
but they can't see each other.

00:58:51.430 --> 00:58:53.650
So Tyson can choose.

00:58:53.650 --> 00:58:55.930
Well, let's just
experiment on some feed.

00:58:55.930 --> 00:58:58.840
We'll try these five
farmers with some new feed

00:58:58.840 --> 00:59:00.550
because they are
forced to take the feed

00:59:00.550 --> 00:59:03.840
and they are forced not to
know what else is happening.

00:59:03.840 --> 00:59:06.960
So think about what this
does to you as a person.

00:59:06.960 --> 00:59:09.210
Don't forget the wage effect.

00:59:09.210 --> 00:59:11.430
But think about the
kind of paranoia

00:59:11.430 --> 00:59:14.760
that arises when you
are subject to the whims

00:59:14.760 --> 00:59:17.400
and experimentation
of this choke point

00:59:17.400 --> 00:59:20.660
upon whom you depend.

00:59:20.660 --> 00:59:22.970
It also brings this
extraordinary amount of fear--

00:59:22.970 --> 00:59:27.230
political fear-- and pockets
where the free speech

00:59:27.230 --> 00:59:30.680
rights that you may be given by
the Constitution don't exist.

00:59:30.680 --> 00:59:34.790
In 2010, when there were a
series of hearings on chicken

00:59:34.790 --> 00:59:37.190
farmers, several people reported
that the chicken farmers

00:59:37.190 --> 00:59:38.780
weren't showing up
for the hearings

00:59:38.780 --> 00:59:41.690
because they're not stupid.

00:59:41.690 --> 00:59:44.383
Perdue can cut them off
and make them go bankrupt

00:59:44.383 --> 00:59:46.550
if they speak up, and they
won't know whether or not

00:59:46.550 --> 00:59:49.670
it's because they
spoke up or not.

00:59:49.670 --> 00:59:53.105
So essentially, this
contract farming,

00:59:53.105 --> 00:59:54.980
which is what it's
called, or chickenization,

00:59:54.980 --> 00:59:56.770
has cut out the farmers tongues.

01:00:00.240 --> 01:00:03.640
This isn't just chicken farming.

01:00:03.640 --> 01:00:05.685
Think about Uber drivers.

01:00:08.700 --> 01:00:12.780
What we see now is in the
realm that we call technology,

01:00:12.780 --> 01:00:16.650
a lot of sort of distraction
around the shiny nature

01:00:16.650 --> 01:00:19.530
of calling various things
technology, which are basically

01:00:19.530 --> 01:00:24.570
just introducing the chicken
farming contract farming model

01:00:24.570 --> 01:00:27.960
to the nature of work.

01:00:27.960 --> 01:00:31.460
So who owns the information in
an Uber kind of relationship?

01:00:31.460 --> 01:00:34.470
Theoretically, the
drivers are free.

01:00:34.470 --> 01:00:37.590
This is the whole sort of story
about the gig economy, which

01:00:37.590 --> 01:00:40.200
is described as
technologically determined as

01:00:40.200 --> 01:00:45.150
opposed to the nature
of market organization.

01:00:45.150 --> 01:00:49.920
But the Uber driver can get
cut off without a reason.

01:00:49.920 --> 01:00:51.727
I talked to some
organizers who--

01:00:51.727 --> 01:00:53.310
I'm hopefully going
to meet him soon--

01:00:53.310 --> 01:00:55.600
but were talking to
an Uber driver who

01:00:55.600 --> 01:00:59.640
was cut off because a
passenger attacked him.

01:00:59.640 --> 01:01:03.377
So because he was engaged
in an altercation,

01:01:03.377 --> 01:01:05.460
Uber said, we don't want
to be anywhere near that.

01:01:05.460 --> 01:01:07.740
But there's no appeal to Uber.

01:01:07.740 --> 01:01:10.560
There's no way to appeal
because Uber is just providing

01:01:10.560 --> 01:01:11.730
this service, this platform.

01:01:11.730 --> 01:01:14.950
It's just in the
private realm, right?

01:01:14.950 --> 01:01:17.570
But like the Tyson
relationship to the farmer,

01:01:17.570 --> 01:01:20.020
there's a fundamental
surveillance panopticon

01:01:20.020 --> 01:01:26.520
relationship happening where
Uber can see all the drivers,

01:01:26.520 --> 01:01:29.280
can choose to
experiment, can choose

01:01:29.280 --> 01:01:32.460
to send them to go
one way or choose

01:01:32.460 --> 01:01:35.100
to experiment in all kinds
of different economic forms.

01:01:35.100 --> 01:01:37.350
They can experiment well or
they can experiment badly.

01:01:37.350 --> 01:01:39.142
By the way, we have to
get rid of this idea

01:01:39.142 --> 01:01:41.430
that just because people
are dominant in the market

01:01:41.430 --> 01:01:43.350
means they're smart.

01:01:43.350 --> 01:01:45.997
World history is littered
with armies marching

01:01:45.997 --> 01:01:46.955
in the wrong direction.

01:01:46.955 --> 01:01:48.580
[LAUGHTER]

01:01:48.580 --> 01:01:50.820
So power does not
mean intelligence,

01:01:50.820 --> 01:01:55.230
but it does being an incredible
new relationship of the worker

01:01:55.230 --> 01:01:58.420
to these choke points.

01:01:58.420 --> 01:02:03.700
Seamless, which
also owns Grubhub,

01:02:03.700 --> 01:02:07.240
they are chickenizing
restaurants.

01:02:07.240 --> 01:02:12.140
Imagine if you go to
Seamless and look for pizza.

01:02:12.140 --> 01:02:16.370
They can disappear
your local restaurant

01:02:16.370 --> 01:02:19.280
by just choosing not
to have them there

01:02:19.280 --> 01:02:22.457
and charge high fees.

01:02:22.457 --> 01:02:24.290
The full scope of that
may not be happening.

01:02:24.290 --> 01:02:26.300
But when we look at
the future, by owning

01:02:26.300 --> 01:02:29.690
what we call the platform,
they have incredible power.

01:02:29.690 --> 01:02:33.050
And they change the relationship
of whether it's the restaurant

01:02:33.050 --> 01:02:38.000
owner or the Uber driver
or the chicken farmer

01:02:38.000 --> 01:02:40.700
not just to their work,
but to their entire life,

01:02:40.700 --> 01:02:42.830
because you are
put in a position

01:02:42.830 --> 01:02:45.340
of informational isolation.

01:02:45.340 --> 01:02:48.410
You're typically contracted
out of the ability to sue.

01:02:48.410 --> 01:02:51.920
Required to go to private courts
called in this gentle language,

01:02:51.920 --> 01:02:55.590
arbitration, alternative
conflict resolution,

01:02:55.590 --> 01:02:59.420
which is basically a form
of privatizing and isolating

01:02:59.420 --> 01:03:03.110
people's legal disputes
from the public.

01:03:03.110 --> 01:03:07.910
So you have isolated,
paranoid, dependent workers.

01:03:07.910 --> 01:03:10.970
And this is the direction
that work is taking.

01:03:10.970 --> 01:03:13.760
More and more, work
is contracted out.

01:03:13.760 --> 01:03:16.190
We can look at it in sort
of gross economic terms.

01:03:16.190 --> 01:03:19.100
And I use "gross" in
both senses of the word.

01:03:19.100 --> 01:03:21.530
[LAUGHTER]

01:03:21.530 --> 01:03:23.600
That more and more
people are moving

01:03:23.600 --> 01:03:26.450
into outsourcing
the liabilities.

01:03:26.450 --> 01:03:30.200
Basically, the Uber driver
takes on the risk of the car.

01:03:30.200 --> 01:03:34.310
The chicken farmer takes on
the risk of the chicken house.

01:03:34.310 --> 01:03:38.120
The restaurant takes on
the risk of all the loans

01:03:38.120 --> 01:03:41.930
and what we call these
platforms, distributors, don't

01:03:41.930 --> 01:03:43.820
take on any of that risk.

01:03:43.820 --> 01:03:45.590
And that's gross in that sense.

01:03:45.590 --> 01:03:49.530
But it's also gross in what
it does to us as people.

01:03:49.530 --> 01:03:53.743
It turns us from a
citizens into denizens.

01:03:53.743 --> 01:03:55.410
Now, what I've been
talking about so far

01:03:55.410 --> 01:03:59.550
are just the minor lords
of our current system.

01:03:59.550 --> 01:04:08.920
The major lords are Amazon,
Google, Facebook, Monsanto,

01:04:08.920 --> 01:04:11.080
Walmart.

01:04:11.080 --> 01:04:14.290
Again, we kind of get
the categories wrong.

01:04:14.290 --> 01:04:18.280
We tend to think about things
in terms of tech or not tech.

01:04:18.280 --> 01:04:20.810
But tech doesn't describe
what is going on.

01:04:20.810 --> 01:04:23.560
First of all, these
are conglomerates.

01:04:23.560 --> 01:04:29.130
Google about a company
a week in 2011.

01:04:29.130 --> 01:04:32.130
Facebook bought Instagram.

01:04:32.130 --> 01:04:39.880
Amazon is a conglomerate of
the Cloud and a platform.

01:04:39.880 --> 01:04:42.730
They're neither
natural nor platforms.

01:04:42.730 --> 01:04:45.510
Even the language of "platform"
and "tech," both of them

01:04:45.510 --> 01:04:47.670
make us think it's
about technology.

01:04:47.670 --> 01:04:50.880
And it's essentially neutral,
but maybe with a little stuff

01:04:50.880 --> 01:04:52.453
at the margins.

01:04:52.453 --> 01:04:53.370
They're not platforms.

01:04:53.370 --> 01:04:55.490
They're choke points.

01:04:55.490 --> 01:04:56.490
And they're not tech.

01:04:56.490 --> 01:04:59.070
They're new business model.

01:04:59.070 --> 01:05:03.120
So if Uber chickenizes
drivers, Amazon

01:05:03.120 --> 01:05:04.740
chickenizes consumer goods.

01:05:07.270 --> 01:05:09.290
Imagine you are Bounty.

01:05:09.290 --> 01:05:11.120
Not that I have any
great love for Bounty.

01:05:11.120 --> 01:05:13.910
They already monopolized or
quasi-monopolized the paper

01:05:13.910 --> 01:05:15.440
towel market.

01:05:15.440 --> 01:05:16.610
They already are a problem.

01:05:16.610 --> 01:05:18.068
So it's not like
we want to go back

01:05:18.068 --> 01:05:20.300
to the good old days of Bounty.

01:05:20.300 --> 01:05:27.620
But Amazon's product
can treat Bounty the way

01:05:27.620 --> 01:05:29.720
that Tyson treats
chicken farmer.

01:05:29.720 --> 01:05:32.260
Spy on it, survey
it, learn from it,

01:05:32.260 --> 01:05:35.660
experiment on it, shift
it around in your answers

01:05:35.660 --> 01:05:39.530
to the question what
paper towels should I buy?

01:05:39.530 --> 01:05:40.430
Squeeze it.

01:05:40.430 --> 01:05:42.830
Demand that Bounty pay its
workers less because they

01:05:42.830 --> 01:05:45.230
know all the information
about Bounty's business model,

01:05:45.230 --> 01:05:51.080
and therefore can say, we're
going to set the price here.

01:05:51.080 --> 01:05:53.950
Because if you want to get
your paper towels to market,

01:05:53.950 --> 01:05:56.450
this is the way they're coming
because you're consumer goods

01:05:56.450 --> 01:05:58.380
and we're Amazon.

01:05:58.380 --> 01:06:00.200
Right?

01:06:00.200 --> 01:06:02.397
But it can also then
study and say, well, we

01:06:02.397 --> 01:06:04.730
want to actually-- now we've
studied Bounty well enough.

01:06:04.730 --> 01:06:07.022
We actually think there's a
pretty decent profit margin

01:06:07.022 --> 01:06:07.610
there.

01:06:07.610 --> 01:06:09.985
We're just going to imitate
Bounty and make our own paper

01:06:09.985 --> 01:06:12.320
towels and sell our
own paper towels.

01:06:12.320 --> 01:06:14.990
So using the producers
of consumer goods

01:06:14.990 --> 01:06:19.040
across the country as
subjects in experiments.

01:06:19.040 --> 01:06:20.270
We talk about citizenship.

01:06:20.270 --> 01:06:22.400
And the opposite of
citizenship is denizenship

01:06:22.400 --> 01:06:25.640
and being subjected.

01:06:25.640 --> 01:06:29.270
So that turns these formerly
free business owners

01:06:29.270 --> 01:06:30.690
into unfree business owners.

01:06:30.690 --> 01:06:34.250
Now, some of them are
terrible business owners.

01:06:34.250 --> 01:06:37.250
But if we do not have
the space for freedom

01:06:37.250 --> 01:06:41.200
in our economic sphere,
there's a real cost there.

01:06:41.200 --> 01:06:44.140
So I want to end with--

01:06:44.140 --> 01:06:49.540
first of all, clearly, we need
a pretty significant revolution

01:06:49.540 --> 01:06:53.320
not only to stop
this growing contract

01:06:53.320 --> 01:06:56.020
farming of the nature of work.

01:06:56.020 --> 01:06:59.050
By the way,
journalists, publishers.

01:06:59.050 --> 01:07:00.790
Who are they
contract farmers for?

01:07:04.030 --> 01:07:07.060
Facebook and Google.

01:07:07.060 --> 01:07:10.770
Facebook can and did
change the algorithm,

01:07:10.770 --> 01:07:14.250
and the Cleveland Plain
Dealer goes out of business.

01:07:14.250 --> 01:07:19.570
It could change it back,
and a news organization

01:07:19.570 --> 01:07:20.890
could come back into business.

01:07:20.890 --> 01:07:24.760
They are essential choke points
that can not only squeeze value

01:07:24.760 --> 01:07:27.010
out of news organizations,
but decide whether or not

01:07:27.010 --> 01:07:28.660
they live or die.

01:07:28.660 --> 01:07:33.250
And by the way, they are trying
to ingratiate ourselves with us

01:07:33.250 --> 01:07:35.680
for recognizing some
degree of their role

01:07:35.680 --> 01:07:42.090
in the murder of journalism by
funding non-profit journalism.

01:07:42.090 --> 01:07:44.870
This is like the tyrant
saying, don't worry.

01:07:44.870 --> 01:07:46.934
I'm putting out my
own publications.

01:07:46.934 --> 01:07:48.710
[LAUGHTER]

01:07:48.710 --> 01:07:51.590
So instead of cheering
them for taking control

01:07:51.590 --> 01:07:54.735
over more of journalism,
we should make sure

01:07:54.735 --> 01:07:56.360
that our central
communications network

01:07:56.360 --> 01:07:58.860
doesn't have this choke
point kind of relationship.

01:07:58.860 --> 01:07:59.360
OK.

01:07:59.360 --> 01:08:03.050
So we clearly need a
radical reformation.

01:08:03.050 --> 01:08:06.350
One of the things
then in this moment--

01:08:06.350 --> 01:08:07.970
which I hope is a
revolutionary moment

01:08:07.970 --> 01:08:11.420
because when [INAUDIBLE]
talks about solidarity,

01:08:11.420 --> 01:08:15.140
I think about the
suicides of taxi drivers

01:08:15.140 --> 01:08:18.050
and the suicides of
farmers, both of whom

01:08:18.050 --> 01:08:20.689
are living in
situations of despair.

01:08:20.689 --> 01:08:22.550
And then if we can
start to as a society

01:08:22.550 --> 01:08:26.840
see that they are both
chickenized in similar ways,

01:08:26.840 --> 01:08:28.760
there's opportunities
for solidarity

01:08:28.760 --> 01:08:32.000
to take on these choke
points that will hopefully

01:08:32.000 --> 01:08:35.450
help this revolution happen.

01:08:35.450 --> 01:08:37.220
One of the things
that I hope that we

01:08:37.220 --> 01:08:39.050
aim for in this
revolution is something

01:08:39.050 --> 01:08:42.760
that the Dalai Lama
tweeted this morning.

01:08:42.760 --> 01:08:49.160
[LAUGHS] He said, "Any idea
that concern for others,

01:08:49.160 --> 01:08:52.340
though a quality, is a
matter for our private lives

01:08:52.340 --> 01:08:53.870
only is short-sighted.

01:08:53.870 --> 01:08:57.890
Compassion belongs to every
sphere of activity, including,

01:08:57.890 --> 01:09:01.420
of course, the workplace."

01:09:01.420 --> 01:09:04.840
Now, this seems like this might
be an uncontroversial topic,

01:09:04.840 --> 01:09:07.899
conceit even on the left.

01:09:07.899 --> 01:09:09.430
But in my last few
minutes, I just

01:09:09.430 --> 01:09:13.689
want to plant the seed that the
idea that the economic sphere

01:09:13.689 --> 01:09:18.720
is a sphere of freedom
and moral development

01:09:18.720 --> 01:09:21.540
is actually a fairly
controversial on both the left

01:09:21.540 --> 01:09:24.703
and right right now.

01:09:24.703 --> 01:09:26.370
You've seen a
transformation on the left

01:09:26.370 --> 01:09:31.020
from Hayek, who saw
the economic sphere

01:09:31.020 --> 01:09:34.229
as a place for essential
moral development

01:09:34.229 --> 01:09:36.960
to the modern
neoliberals like Gautier,

01:09:36.960 --> 01:09:40.170
who say that basically moral
development should happen

01:09:40.170 --> 01:09:42.300
outside the economic sphere.

01:09:42.300 --> 01:09:44.670
We should be radically
profit maximizing

01:09:44.670 --> 01:09:47.640
so that we can maximize
efficiencies and then

01:09:47.640 --> 01:09:50.729
go be moral elsewhere.

01:09:50.729 --> 01:09:56.460
Be moral in our church
lives, in our community life,

01:09:56.460 --> 01:09:57.780
in our private lives.

01:09:57.780 --> 01:10:00.870
Morality belongs to
the private sphere.

01:10:00.870 --> 01:10:04.380
But you actually see a
mirror image in many thinkers

01:10:04.380 --> 01:10:07.770
on the left who have
basically given up the market

01:10:07.770 --> 01:10:10.200
as an irredeemable space.

01:10:10.200 --> 01:10:13.380
They fundamentally
associate the language

01:10:13.380 --> 01:10:16.320
of markets, the
fact of a market,

01:10:16.320 --> 01:10:20.610
the fact of a kind
of private exchange

01:10:20.610 --> 01:10:25.440
with a radical
corruption of morality.

01:10:25.440 --> 01:10:29.490
And we see this in basically
Sandel fighting with Sandel.

01:10:29.490 --> 01:10:31.260
I say that because
I'm at Harvard,

01:10:31.260 --> 01:10:32.880
for those of you who know him.

01:10:32.880 --> 01:10:34.500
There's an old
Sandel who believed

01:10:34.500 --> 01:10:36.333
in the redeemability
of markets, and there's

01:10:36.333 --> 01:10:40.800
a new Sandel who in 2012 wrote
a book about the corruption

01:10:40.800 --> 01:10:43.560
that markets have in
our private sphere,

01:10:43.560 --> 01:10:47.040
assuming that market logic
was necessarily immoral,

01:10:47.040 --> 01:10:49.710
or at best, amoral logic.

01:10:49.710 --> 01:10:52.950
And I think what we have
to do is as we reconstruct

01:10:52.950 --> 01:10:56.850
a new economy, reconstruct
meaningful freedom, including

01:10:56.850 --> 01:11:01.290
moral freedom, embedded so
that we can just be paid well,

01:11:01.290 --> 01:11:03.930
but be compassionate and
loving in our private

01:11:03.930 --> 01:11:05.652
and our economic life.

01:11:05.652 --> 01:11:06.152
Thank you.

01:11:06.152 --> 01:11:09.624
[APPLAUSE]

01:11:18.560 --> 01:11:22.150
- So all of our panelists
have in some ways

01:11:22.150 --> 01:11:24.190
complicated the
conventional narrative

01:11:24.190 --> 01:11:28.570
of economics citizenship that
I introduced the panel with.

01:11:28.570 --> 01:11:30.122
I'd like to do two things.

01:11:30.122 --> 01:11:32.080
I think we want to have
some limited discussion

01:11:32.080 --> 01:11:33.130
among the panel.

01:11:33.130 --> 01:11:36.477
I'd like to get all three of
you talking to one another.

01:11:36.477 --> 01:11:38.560
And then after that, we're
going to take questions

01:11:38.560 --> 01:11:40.240
from the audience.

01:11:40.240 --> 01:11:47.285
And four questions came to mind
as I listened to your remarks.

01:11:47.285 --> 01:11:49.160
And you don't have to
respond to my question.

01:11:49.160 --> 01:11:50.410
You can respond to each other.

01:11:50.410 --> 01:11:51.370
It doesn't matter.

01:11:51.370 --> 01:11:54.190
But here's four quick questions.

01:11:54.190 --> 01:12:00.490
There's a tension in your
presentations between critiques

01:12:00.490 --> 01:12:03.260
of dominant discourses
of economic citizenship,

01:12:03.260 --> 01:12:07.150
be they discourses
grounded in notions

01:12:07.150 --> 01:12:12.620
of US citizenship, which is
sort of imposed from above;

01:12:12.620 --> 01:12:15.320
economic citizenship
imposed by corporations;

01:12:15.320 --> 01:12:17.770
and citizenship from
the perspective of those

01:12:17.770 --> 01:12:18.970
who are dominated.

01:12:22.570 --> 01:12:26.350
How do we sort of get
both on the table?

01:12:26.350 --> 01:12:31.210
Related to this,
particular, Rosita Worl

01:12:31.210 --> 01:12:35.050
reminds us that there are many
forms of economic citizenship

01:12:35.050 --> 01:12:37.810
which have been used
by the subalterns

01:12:37.810 --> 01:12:40.780
to mobilize alternative
frameworks for citizenship.

01:12:40.780 --> 01:12:44.950
I mean, this complicated,
complex question

01:12:44.950 --> 01:12:50.180
of native citizenship in Alaska,
the corporation of the tribes,

01:12:50.180 --> 01:12:51.610
the clans.

01:12:51.610 --> 01:12:54.610
Of course, the Alaska
Native Claims Settlement Act

01:12:54.610 --> 01:12:57.130
is a congressional statute.

01:12:57.130 --> 01:12:59.770
Of course, it's in some measure
imposed from above all those.

01:12:59.770 --> 01:13:01.960
But yeah, it's complicated.

01:13:01.960 --> 01:13:03.670
