01:27:01.550 --> 01:27:03.620
the bill was based
on a model bill

01:27:03.620 --> 01:27:06.590
created by ALEC, which many
of you may be familiar with.

01:27:06.590 --> 01:27:10.700
The American Legislative
Exchange Council.

01:27:10.700 --> 01:27:17.360
At the time, ALEC was funded
by AT&amp;T, Google, Amazon,

01:27:17.360 --> 01:27:20.580
all of these
different characters.

01:27:20.580 --> 01:27:23.330
One of the more successful
anti corporate efforts

01:27:23.330 --> 01:27:29.510
in recent years was an effort to
get many of those corporations

01:27:29.510 --> 01:27:32.150
to stop funding ALEC.

01:27:32.150 --> 01:27:34.870
But the truth is they
did in the first place.

01:27:34.870 --> 01:27:36.530
And it took a lot of--

01:27:36.530 --> 01:27:39.830
eventually actually left
ALEC largely because

01:27:39.830 --> 01:27:43.820
of ALEC's funding of stand
your ground gun laws.

01:27:43.820 --> 01:27:47.030
But we're relatively
comfortable funding ALEC,

01:27:47.030 --> 01:27:49.460
saying it was because
of other reasons

01:27:49.460 --> 01:27:55.370
while ALEC was involved in
aggressively pushing the most

01:27:55.370 --> 01:28:02.900
draconian explicitly race
based voter suppression

01:28:02.900 --> 01:28:04.370
law in the country.

01:28:07.150 --> 01:28:09.520
And I think it's important
because we sometimes

01:28:09.520 --> 01:28:11.710
will look at a place like--

01:28:11.710 --> 01:28:13.960
well, anywhere-- but
like North Carolina

01:28:13.960 --> 01:28:20.410
and hold up the lawmakers
who are pushing it

01:28:20.410 --> 01:28:24.160
as the primary drivers.

01:28:24.160 --> 01:28:25.960
But we have to
understand that one

01:28:25.960 --> 01:28:30.910
of the key drivers inflaming
racial hatred and division

01:28:30.910 --> 01:28:34.270
in North Carolina was AT&amp;T,
Google, and the other funders

01:28:34.270 --> 01:28:35.030
in this case.

01:28:35.030 --> 01:28:38.530
And meanwhile, AT&amp;T is
also funding the NAACP.

01:28:38.530 --> 01:28:40.050
So it's kind of a double--

01:28:40.050 --> 01:28:42.940
making sure the fingers
are in every pot.

01:28:42.940 --> 01:28:44.890
What they'll say
is well, we just

01:28:44.890 --> 01:28:47.680
want to make sure that
nobody can sue anybody.

01:28:47.680 --> 01:28:49.360
I mean, a lot of
the reasons people

01:28:49.360 --> 01:28:52.630
fund ALEC is because of their--

01:28:52.630 --> 01:28:55.420
they want put it like that--
but [LAUGHS] a lot of reasons

01:28:55.420 --> 01:29:00.760
the big corporations fund ALEC
is to gut access to the courts.

01:29:00.760 --> 01:29:02.200
And it's just detritus.

01:29:02.200 --> 01:29:03.850
It's just sort of a
side effect that we

01:29:03.850 --> 01:29:05.500
were suppressing the vote.

01:29:05.500 --> 01:29:08.885
But I think that's
not acceptable.

01:29:08.885 --> 01:29:12.140
[LAUGHS]

01:29:12.140 --> 01:29:16.100
- My question go-- first of
all, my name is Julia Carpenter.

01:29:16.100 --> 01:29:18.740
And communication--
and I don't know

01:29:18.740 --> 01:29:22.280
if you've heard the Ted
Talk about "the other"

01:29:22.280 --> 01:29:25.690
where we can't seem
to talk to each other.

01:29:25.690 --> 01:29:29.090
It's not just a matter of not
being able to see the person.

01:29:29.090 --> 01:29:31.860
It's like when you see them,
there's no communication.

01:29:31.860 --> 01:29:32.630
Nobody listens.

01:29:32.630 --> 01:29:34.570
Everybody's talking.

01:29:34.570 --> 01:29:37.330
How do we communicate?

01:29:37.330 --> 01:29:43.960
For instance, PBS,
NPR, all of that--

01:29:43.960 --> 01:29:47.920
the funding of that, you don't
know where that's coming from.

01:29:47.920 --> 01:29:52.370
You don't know the
influences behind the screen.

01:29:52.370 --> 01:29:54.760
How do you keep up
to date or how do you

01:29:54.760 --> 01:29:58.360
communicate to get
people to come together

01:29:58.360 --> 01:30:02.155
and to act together?

01:30:02.155 --> 01:30:03.590
[INTERPOSING VOICES]

01:30:03.590 --> 01:30:04.280
- Only that.

01:30:04.280 --> 01:30:05.780
[LAUGHTER]

01:30:05.780 --> 01:30:10.730
Well, for starters, this is not
a complete answer, but it is,

01:30:10.730 --> 01:30:13.550
I think, a partial,
essential answer.

01:30:13.550 --> 01:30:16.730
Too, we have essential
communications infrastructure

01:30:16.730 --> 01:30:17.360
in our country.

01:30:20.950 --> 01:30:24.150
Telephone company, the mail.

01:30:24.150 --> 01:30:27.290
Imagine if the American
mail service started out

01:30:27.290 --> 01:30:31.610
as a surveillance model that
basically the way that mail

01:30:31.610 --> 01:30:33.740
carriers were
going to make money

01:30:33.740 --> 01:30:36.650
is by reading
everybody's mail and then

01:30:36.650 --> 01:30:41.750
pitching them whatever goods
was the best way to pitch them.

01:30:41.750 --> 01:30:43.380
We would find that
kind of problematic.

01:30:43.380 --> 01:30:44.960
It's necessarily
going to distort

01:30:44.960 --> 01:30:49.010
the flow of mail and
shape what happens

01:30:49.010 --> 01:30:51.080
in that essential
communications infrastructure.

01:30:51.080 --> 01:30:52.955
Well, right now, we have
Google and Facebook,

01:30:52.955 --> 01:30:55.640
two essential communications
infrastructure,

01:30:55.640 --> 01:30:58.310
whose entire business
model is based

01:30:58.310 --> 01:31:02.100
on surveillance and sales.

01:31:02.100 --> 01:31:05.863
So it's almost like if you had
an essential transportation

01:31:05.863 --> 01:31:06.530
infrastructure--

01:31:06.530 --> 01:31:08.900
I think maybe the easier
model for me was the bus.

01:31:08.900 --> 01:31:11.720
If our buses made
money off surveillance,

01:31:11.720 --> 01:31:14.630
they would, first of all, keep
us in the bus a lot longer,

01:31:14.630 --> 01:31:15.532
right?

01:31:15.532 --> 01:31:17.240
So you have to stay
in the bus as long as

01:31:17.240 --> 01:31:18.865
possible because then
they can overhear

01:31:18.865 --> 01:31:22.680
our conversations more and be
focused on selling you stuff.

01:31:22.680 --> 01:31:25.190
Well, right now, we have
Facebook and Google,

01:31:25.190 --> 01:31:28.460
whose incentive is
to make us addicted

01:31:28.460 --> 01:31:31.280
and to surveil us and
make money off us.

01:31:31.280 --> 01:31:33.350
We do not have to have
essential communications

01:31:33.350 --> 01:31:34.580
infrastructure
that is distorting

01:31:34.580 --> 01:31:35.747
our information in this way.

01:31:35.747 --> 01:31:36.830
We don't have to.

01:31:36.830 --> 01:31:38.810
We didn't have to have
a mail service that way.

01:31:38.810 --> 01:31:40.640
We didn't have to have a
phone service that way.

01:31:40.640 --> 01:31:43.190
And we can say that essential
communications infrastructure

01:31:43.190 --> 01:31:44.592
cannot be surveillance based.

01:31:44.592 --> 01:31:46.550
You cannot have a digital
ad based surveillance

01:31:46.550 --> 01:31:47.175
infrastructure.

01:31:47.175 --> 01:31:48.020
We can do that.

01:31:48.020 --> 01:31:50.630
It's not a complete answer, but
it sure would help as a start.

01:31:54.395 --> 01:31:55.020
- Anybody else?

01:31:55.020 --> 01:31:56.662
Communication?

01:31:56.662 --> 01:31:58.370
- Well, you would
think this is something

01:31:58.370 --> 01:32:00.700
I would know and could master.

01:32:00.700 --> 01:32:06.020
Because in Alaska, we have
our native versus non-native.

01:32:06.020 --> 01:32:10.310
We have our rural versus urban.

01:32:10.310 --> 01:32:14.930
And the lack of
communication has

01:32:14.930 --> 01:32:17.460
been a great problem for us.

01:32:17.460 --> 01:32:21.950
And for my own
little organization,

01:32:21.950 --> 01:32:24.350
we said that we
adopted a mission

01:32:24.350 --> 01:32:27.110
to promote cross-cultural
understanding

01:32:27.110 --> 01:32:30.860
and support cultural diversity.

01:32:30.860 --> 01:32:34.460
And we had to
spend a lot of time

01:32:34.460 --> 01:32:38.810
educating non-native
people about who we are.

01:32:38.810 --> 01:32:42.860
And I actually have to pay
teachers to come in and take

01:32:42.860 --> 01:32:45.380
courses from us to learn,
because we pay them,

01:32:45.380 --> 01:32:47.043
and they can get their credit.

01:32:47.043 --> 01:32:49.460
And they're really important
because they're the ones that

01:32:49.460 --> 01:32:52.160
teach our children.

01:32:52.160 --> 01:32:54.710
And so in Alaska,
we've spent tons

01:32:54.710 --> 01:32:58.160
of money trying to
reach out to the other,

01:32:58.160 --> 01:32:59.960
to educate them about--

01:32:59.960 --> 01:33:02.930
like our hunting
and fishing rights.

01:33:02.930 --> 01:33:05.690
We still are dependent
on hunting and fishing

01:33:05.690 --> 01:33:08.390
for our survival, plus
a cultural attachment

01:33:08.390 --> 01:33:09.200
to the land.

01:33:09.200 --> 01:33:13.970
But we have commercial
hunters and fishers,

01:33:13.970 --> 01:33:19.970
and we have sports people
that control everything.

01:33:19.970 --> 01:33:25.220
We take only 2% of hunting
and fishing resources

01:33:25.220 --> 01:33:27.950
for our subsistence purposes.

01:33:27.950 --> 01:33:32.770
But yet people want to--
they talk about equality,

01:33:32.770 --> 01:33:38.210
this whole issue of equality
and say we have to be all equal.

01:33:38.210 --> 01:33:40.010
And I said, well,
OK, I like that.

01:33:40.010 --> 01:33:43.080
How about if we have one
third of all the fisheries

01:33:43.080 --> 01:33:44.240
and resources?

01:33:44.240 --> 01:33:46.640
Because right now,
we're only getting 2%?

01:33:46.640 --> 01:33:47.960
But I don't know.

01:33:47.960 --> 01:33:50.030
It's just something
that we live and breathe

01:33:50.030 --> 01:33:52.910
with all of the time,
trying to reach out.

01:33:52.910 --> 01:33:58.460
How do we get to
communicate with people?

01:33:58.460 --> 01:34:01.530
And I was thinking about the
other question that was asked.

01:34:01.530 --> 01:34:05.690
For the last three
or four censuses,

01:34:05.690 --> 01:34:08.570
when we do a
reapportionment, I've

01:34:08.570 --> 01:34:13.640
sat on that reapportionment
board for about four times

01:34:13.640 --> 01:34:19.010
trying to make sure that we
could have our votes protected,

01:34:19.010 --> 01:34:22.100
our rights to vote, and
making our votes count.

01:34:22.100 --> 01:34:26.310
And to me, it feels like
I'm always in a battle.

01:34:26.310 --> 01:34:29.750
I'm always in a battle
trying to maintain my rights

01:34:29.750 --> 01:34:30.710
as a citizen.

01:34:30.710 --> 01:34:32.780
And I don't have
all the answers,

01:34:32.780 --> 01:34:34.010
but we just keep trying.

01:34:34.010 --> 01:34:37.408
And we keep trying
to talk to people.

01:34:37.408 --> 01:34:38.450
I don't know the answers.

01:34:41.230 --> 01:34:42.080
- Good morning.

01:34:42.080 --> 01:34:44.090
My name is Ned Bacon.

01:34:44.090 --> 01:34:48.740
Three of four of you are
active participants and deeply

01:34:48.740 --> 01:34:51.080
invested in higher education.

01:34:51.080 --> 01:34:53.330
Higher education
particularly in our country

01:34:53.330 --> 01:35:00.380
is a major choke point
to economic citizenship.

01:35:00.380 --> 01:35:05.120
And I'd be very interested in
your three personal thoughts

01:35:05.120 --> 01:35:09.290
about that as well as maybe
some policy solutions that

01:35:09.290 --> 01:35:17.270
would get our country to a more
public good aspect of education

01:35:17.270 --> 01:35:20.540
the way you see it in places
like Norway and other developed

01:35:20.540 --> 01:35:21.200
economies.

01:35:24.984 --> 01:35:27.350
- Anybody?

01:35:27.350 --> 01:35:30.020
- Well, again, this is
something that we live

01:35:30.020 --> 01:35:33.950
and breathe is education
and higher education.

01:35:33.950 --> 01:35:38.450
And we've attacked it
on different realms.

01:35:38.450 --> 01:35:42.050
Number one, by providing
a lot of scholarships

01:35:42.050 --> 01:35:44.150
from our native corporations.

01:35:44.150 --> 01:35:48.440
And so all of our corporations
have scholarship programs,

01:35:48.440 --> 01:35:51.170
but that's not enough.

01:35:51.170 --> 01:35:54.830
We know that we have a lot
of academic deficiencies.

01:35:54.830 --> 01:35:57.950
And so we spend a lot of our
time teaching-- like math.

01:35:57.950 --> 01:36:01.670
I found out that our native kids
weren't making it into college

01:36:01.670 --> 01:36:02.840
because they couldn't pass.

01:36:02.840 --> 01:36:07.280
They got into Cal College,
but couldn't pass Math 106.

01:36:07.280 --> 01:36:10.580
So we started math
programs all over,

01:36:10.580 --> 01:36:13.700
teaching, but using
our cultural base.

01:36:13.700 --> 01:36:17.000
So we would teach
math in a basket.

01:36:17.000 --> 01:36:21.020
We would teach around our
own kinds of technology.

01:36:21.020 --> 01:36:23.600
We would teach math around
the environment, things

01:36:23.600 --> 01:36:27.410
that our children saw and lived.

01:36:27.410 --> 01:36:30.500
We would make it relevant
to their experiences.

01:36:30.500 --> 01:36:32.180
But then we also
found out you know

01:36:32.180 --> 01:36:34.460
that we have to take over
the university system.

01:36:34.460 --> 01:36:38.240
So [LAUGHS] we started
putting our people

01:36:38.240 --> 01:36:40.340
on the board of regions.

01:36:40.340 --> 01:36:47.480
And I mean, you have to be
able to control those systems

01:36:47.480 --> 01:36:49.640
to make it work for you.

01:36:49.640 --> 01:36:54.095
Otherwise, if you don't,
you're going to have--

01:36:54.095 --> 01:36:56.870
well, some of you might like
charter schools and things

01:36:56.870 --> 01:36:57.830
like that.

01:36:57.830 --> 01:37:03.080
I found out that it only goes
for those who have the means

01:37:03.080 --> 01:37:04.640
to go to charter schools.

01:37:04.640 --> 01:37:07.400
When we were working
on our education,

01:37:07.400 --> 01:37:10.370
our native teachers
came and said--

01:37:10.370 --> 01:37:12.410
I said, should we start
our own charter school?

01:37:12.410 --> 01:37:13.460
They said, nope.

01:37:13.460 --> 01:37:16.880
You have to work to make
education good for all

01:37:16.880 --> 01:37:18.230
of our children.

01:37:18.230 --> 01:37:21.890
And so you have to attack it
at multiple levels for higher

01:37:21.890 --> 01:37:22.650
education.

01:37:22.650 --> 01:37:25.490
This is not only
scholarships, but it's also

01:37:25.490 --> 01:37:31.130
seeing what is preventing our
children from moving forward.

01:37:31.130 --> 01:37:33.980
If it's reintroducing
and changing

01:37:33.980 --> 01:37:39.170
the curricula at the high
school and even earlier.

01:37:39.170 --> 01:37:41.810
We have a Baby
Raven Reads project

01:37:41.810 --> 01:37:44.410
where we're teaching our
children how to read.

01:37:44.410 --> 01:37:47.270
But the other part of it is
also teaching our parents

01:37:47.270 --> 01:37:48.560
how to be good parents.

01:37:48.560 --> 01:37:53.000
A lot of our people were taken
and put into boarding schools.

01:37:53.000 --> 01:37:55.640
And so they never learned
how to be parents.

01:37:55.640 --> 01:37:59.300
So the school was
something that was--

01:37:59.300 --> 01:38:01.680
parenting was kind
of alien to them.

01:38:01.680 --> 01:38:04.880
And I just can't believe
that for us as native people,

01:38:04.880 --> 01:38:06.890
how we love and
cherish families.

01:38:06.890 --> 01:38:09.440
But we didn't have
the basic mechanics.

01:38:09.440 --> 01:38:13.310
So, again, it's
at multiple levels

01:38:13.310 --> 01:38:16.800
that you have to attack
issue of higher education.

01:38:16.800 --> 01:38:21.800
- I'll just add really quickly,
the defunding of our higher

01:38:21.800 --> 01:38:25.100
education-- so the defunding of
the system of higher education

01:38:25.100 --> 01:38:28.187
the last few decades
has coincided with--

01:38:28.187 --> 01:38:30.020
and it's not a coincidence--
with the moment

01:38:30.020 --> 01:38:35.330
at which the cohort of students
attending higher education

01:38:35.330 --> 01:38:37.940
is the most racially
diverse cohort

01:38:37.940 --> 01:38:39.770
in the history of the country.

01:38:39.770 --> 01:38:41.870
And so what you
are actually facing

01:38:41.870 --> 01:38:43.610
is this is one of
those front lines

01:38:43.610 --> 01:38:45.920
for that kind of unequal
membership, I think,

01:38:45.920 --> 01:38:47.648
that we are all talking about.

01:38:47.648 --> 01:38:49.190
What we actually
have now is a system

01:38:49.190 --> 01:38:50.930
of higher education
that is highly

01:38:50.930 --> 01:38:53.335
tiered by race and by class.

01:38:53.335 --> 01:38:54.960
When you think about
the ways in which,

01:38:54.960 --> 01:38:56.690
say, for profit
colleges are subbing

01:38:56.690 --> 01:39:01.010
in for a defunded public
higher education system

01:39:01.010 --> 01:39:06.600
and how extractive those for
profit college mechanisms are.

01:39:06.600 --> 01:39:10.055
And then when you think about
the way in which by design,

01:39:10.055 --> 01:39:11.930
public policy, especially
the last few years,

01:39:11.930 --> 01:39:15.560
has tried to further defund
the public education system

01:39:15.560 --> 01:39:19.580
and unleash that type of
predatory higher education

01:39:19.580 --> 01:39:20.210
policies.

01:39:20.210 --> 01:39:22.190
And so in terms of
solution, I mean,

01:39:22.190 --> 01:39:24.050
I think there's a lot
of-- in the same way

01:39:24.050 --> 01:39:26.340
that there's a big debate
right now about health

01:39:26.340 --> 01:39:30.410
care and universal access to
health care, debt free college,

01:39:30.410 --> 01:39:33.440
and tuition free college,
and different ways, I think,

01:39:33.440 --> 01:39:37.530
are a key part of
that policy fight.

01:39:37.530 --> 01:39:39.680
There's a good argument
that the focus really

01:39:39.680 --> 01:39:42.320
should be on debt free rather
than just tuition free.

01:39:42.320 --> 01:39:45.020
Because when you add up all
the different ways in which

01:39:45.020 --> 01:39:47.450
the financialized
higher education system

01:39:47.450 --> 01:39:52.880
can create decade's worth
of economic suppression

01:39:52.880 --> 01:39:56.240
for people, especially low
income students and students

01:39:56.240 --> 01:39:58.940
of color who have to bear
the burden of student debt

01:39:58.940 --> 01:40:00.110
for the rest of their lives.

01:40:00.110 --> 01:40:02.370
We're in a student debt
crisis in this country.

01:40:02.370 --> 01:40:05.850
And that's part of what
needs to be solved.

01:40:05.850 --> 01:40:06.350
- OK.

01:40:09.710 --> 01:40:10.890
- [CLEARS THROAT] Hi.

01:40:10.890 --> 01:40:13.170
My name's Heather Hoffman.

01:40:13.170 --> 01:40:20.430
And I'm here to ask for help
in getting my fellow residents

01:40:20.430 --> 01:40:25.650
of this gorgeous city to believe
that not only is democracy not

01:40:25.650 --> 01:40:30.720
a spectator sport, but
that they should take part.

01:40:30.720 --> 01:40:33.840
Not just here, but
across the country,

01:40:33.840 --> 01:40:37.020
we're turning government
over to private corporations

01:40:37.020 --> 01:40:38.880
in so many ways.

01:40:38.880 --> 01:40:43.560
You can think of things
like athletic stadiums

01:40:43.560 --> 01:40:47.880
where we take people's land so
the government can turn it over

01:40:47.880 --> 01:40:51.600
to a private corporation
that has enough money

01:40:51.600 --> 01:40:54.150
to pay people millions and
millions of dollars a year

01:40:54.150 --> 01:40:56.340
to play.

01:40:56.340 --> 01:41:02.580
Locally, we have things like a
toxic courthouse that is toxic

01:41:02.580 --> 01:41:04.230
not just because of
the toxics in it,

01:41:04.230 --> 01:41:07.470
but toxic because
it's gigantic compared

01:41:07.470 --> 01:41:09.580
to the neighborhood around it.

01:41:09.580 --> 01:41:12.103
And the only way the
Commonwealth of Massachusetts

01:41:12.103 --> 01:41:13.770
and the city of
Cambridge can figure out

01:41:13.770 --> 01:41:15.870
how to deal with it
is to turn it over

01:41:15.870 --> 01:41:17.160
to a private corporation.

01:41:17.160 --> 01:41:19.920
And then because
that's not enough,

01:41:19.920 --> 01:41:22.140
have to turn over
more public property

01:41:22.140 --> 01:41:24.610
to a private corporation.

01:41:24.610 --> 01:41:28.000
And what I see of my fellow
citizens is a whole lot of what

01:41:28.000 --> 01:41:29.330
can we do about it?

01:41:29.330 --> 01:41:32.950
So what are ways
to convince people

01:41:32.950 --> 01:41:35.830
that we deserve to
be treated better

01:41:35.830 --> 01:41:39.420
and that we can demand it?

01:41:39.420 --> 01:41:39.980
- Yeah.

01:41:39.980 --> 01:41:42.240
That's a great question.

01:41:42.240 --> 01:41:43.470
Two things I'd say.

01:41:43.470 --> 01:41:48.510
I mean, one is that cycle that
you're describing actually even

01:41:48.510 --> 01:41:51.960
starts even further
back with the defunding

01:41:51.960 --> 01:41:55.860
of the kind of public
arena more broadly, right?

01:41:55.860 --> 01:42:00.150
Cut taxes, then there's less
revenue at the city and state

01:42:00.150 --> 01:42:02.880
level, then that forces
a kind of austerity

01:42:02.880 --> 01:42:04.710
for state and local
policies, which

01:42:04.710 --> 01:42:09.150
then seems to require the
privatization [CLEARS THROAT]

01:42:09.150 --> 01:42:13.090
of those things that we think
are central to a public.

01:42:13.090 --> 01:42:16.950
Public schools, public
goods of all kinds.

01:42:16.950 --> 01:42:19.980
And so there's a resource
question at the very back.

01:42:19.980 --> 01:42:21.450
But the wealth is there.

01:42:21.450 --> 01:42:25.030
It's just now locked away
and hoarded in other pockets,

01:42:25.030 --> 01:42:25.530
right?

01:42:25.530 --> 01:42:29.100
And so if you add up all the
resources available to us

01:42:29.100 --> 01:42:32.070
as a country, it's just
not being channeled

01:42:32.070 --> 01:42:34.200
into public investments.

01:42:34.200 --> 01:42:38.220
So there's a policy answer
in terms of how to get there.

01:42:38.220 --> 01:42:40.470
I mean, I'd actually argue
that it's less about people

01:42:40.470 --> 01:42:43.470
being apathetic and
not being interested

01:42:43.470 --> 01:42:45.730
in the issue and
more that people

01:42:45.730 --> 01:42:48.000
don't believe that
we're actually

01:42:48.000 --> 01:42:50.250
going to be able to win, right?

01:42:50.250 --> 01:42:53.970
And that I think
just means zeroing in

01:42:53.970 --> 01:42:57.080
on the kinds of puppet
masters behind the scenes

01:42:57.080 --> 01:42:58.330
that Zephyr was talking about.

01:42:58.330 --> 01:43:02.340
There are deliberate
class interests

01:43:02.340 --> 01:43:04.710
and corporate interests
at play that benefit

01:43:04.710 --> 01:43:07.020
from a defunded public sector.

01:43:07.020 --> 01:43:11.610
And often, lurking behind
many layers of shell companies

01:43:11.610 --> 01:43:12.470
and kind of--

01:43:12.470 --> 01:43:14.910
you have to kind of trace
it all the way back.

01:43:14.910 --> 01:43:17.370
So I think part of
it is identifying who

01:43:17.370 --> 01:43:18.880
the villains are in the story.

01:43:18.880 --> 01:43:19.380
All right?

01:43:19.380 --> 01:43:22.290
And then making the
case not just that

01:43:22.290 --> 01:43:24.330
this ought to be
something that we do,

01:43:24.330 --> 01:43:25.975
but that it's
actually achievable.

01:43:25.975 --> 01:43:28.380
And part of what's
potentially exciting I think

01:43:28.380 --> 01:43:29.838
about the debate
we're having right

01:43:29.838 --> 01:43:33.420
